1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 {[%csl Rc4]} {As I mentioned in the
introduction to Slav defense, the only drawback of direct approach with 3.Nf3
and 4.Nc3 is c4 pawn being unprotected. In the Classical Slav, black
immediately tries to take advantage of that fact by taking the pawn:} dxc4 {
[%cal Gb7b5] and threatening to hold on to it with b7-b5 in case of 5.e4 or 5.
e3. Practice has shown that the best way for white to fight for advantage is
to deny black this option with:} 5. a4 (5. e4 b5 {[%csl Gc4]} 6. e5 Nd5 7. a4
$13) (5. e3 b5 6. a4 b4 7. Na2 (7. Nb1 Ba6 $13) 7... e6 8. Bxc4 Be7 $11 {[%csl
Ra2][%cal Gc8b7,Gc6c5]}) {As black will not do well by trying to hold on to
his extra pawn by means other than b7-b5 (ideas like Be6 or Qa5-b4 are too
sketchy), he is best advised to continue his development. Before we look at
his developing options, let us take stock of the previous move. Black has
given up the control of e4 square by playing dxc4, while white has done the
same with b4 square by playing a2-a4. Therefore, both sides have made a small
concession. However, compared to a move ago (position after 4.Nc3), black is
now able to develop his c8-bishop freely because white does not have the
annoying Qb3 any more. Since he has given up control of the e4 square by
playing dxc4, the most logical continuation is to take this square under
control with 4...Bf5 and that is indeed the most common move in this position.}
5... Bf5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf5e4]} ({Most notable alternatives are:} 5... e6 {
[%cal Gc6c5] preparing c6-c5 break, aiming for the Queen's gambit accepted
kind of position. We will cover it in Chapter 2.}) (5... Bg4 {[%cal Gd8d4,
Gg4d1] developing the bishop to a more active square and discouraging e2-e4 by
indirect means.}) (5... Na6 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Ga6b4] preparing to bring the
knight to the weakened b4 square (normally the bishop goes there and the
knight to d7).}) ({and} 5... a5 6. e4 Bg4 7. Bxc4 $14 {which is a solid
fighting line with little theory compared to other lines. All these less
challenging variations will be covered in Chapter 1 to give you a taste of the
typical Classical Slav positions, before we move on to the more complex
theoretical material in the following chapters.}) {White now has 3
possibilites: 6.Ne5, 6.e3 and 6.Nh4. We recommend the first one:} 6. Ne5 {The
idea of this move is twofold: taking the c4 pawn with the knight and preparing
f3, e4 (sometimes g3, Bg2, e4) to gain control of the vital e4 square. 
Compared to 6.e3, which is the main alternative, this is a more ambitious,
sort of a high risk/high reward approach.} (6. e3 {is a slower move, aiming to
complete development with Bxc4 and 0-0 before undertaking any actions in the
center.} e6 {[%cal Gf1c4]} 7. Bxc4 Bb4 {[%csl Gb4]} 8. O-O O-O {Then white
usually fights for e4 square with} 9. Qe2 {[%cal Ge3e4] and the main line goes:
} Nbd7 10. e4 Bg6 $14 {/=  where black's solidity and lack of weaknesses
compensate for white's spatial advantage.}) (6. Nh4 {is an exciting
alternative, though less principled than the first two. Black usually play} e6
({An interesting alternative, if black is happy with a draw (which he usually
is when he plays the Classical slav) is} 6... Bc8 $5 {[%csl Rh4] highlighting
bad position of white knight} 7. e3 (7. e4 e5 $1 $132 {[%csl Rh4]}) (7. Nf3 Bf5
$11 {is move repetition}) 7... Bg4 $1 $13) {and after} 7. Nxf5 exf5 {[%csl Gb4,
Gf5][%cal Gf5e4,Gf8b4] he gets a pawn structure where bishop on f5 is replaced
with the pawn and black's good control of central squares yields him
reasonable chances in the arising middlegame positions:} 8. e3 Bb4 9. Bxc4 O-O
10. O-O Nbd7 $13 {[%csl Yc1,Yc4,Gd5,Ge4][%cal Rf5e4,Rc6d5]}) {Against 6.Ne5,
Black has two natural moves: 6...Nbd7 and 6...e6, plus 6...Na6, which is a
decent sideline. The most popular move, which was considered the main line
even in Alekhine's and Capablanca's time is:} 6... Nbd7 ({The alternative is} 
6... e6 {[%cal Gf8b4]} 7. f3 {[%cal Ge2e4]} Bb4 {with an enterprising idea to
fight 8.e2-e4 with a piece sacrifice 8...Bxe4!?} ({There is another move here,
which on the contrary leads to a quiet endgame after} 7... c5 8. e4 Bg6 (8...
cxd4 {is an attempt to complicate matters, but it has been more or less
refuted by now, which we will see in more detail in Chapter 3.}) 9. Be3 cxd4
10. Qxd4 Qxd4 11. Bxd4 Nfd7 12. Nxd7 Nxd7 13. Bxc4 {[%csl Rg6] Black have
chosen to defend this endgame in two recent matches for the World Championship.
Indeed, drawing percentage has been high for black here, but white can make
black's life difficult with accurate play, as we will see in Chapter 3.}) {
Instead of the sharp line with 8.e4, we recommend a simpler solution:} 8. Nxc4
(8. e4 Bxe4 $5 9. fxe4 Nxe4 10. Bd2 Qxd4 11. Nxe4 Qxe4+ 12. Qe2 Bxd2+ 13. Kxd2
Qd5+ {leads to some very strange positions where black usually has three pawns
for the piece in the endgame.}) 8... O-O 9. Kf2 $5 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Ge2e4]
This peculiar idea, analyzed in Chapter 4, is less explored than the main line
with 8.e4, but is nevertheless putting black under a serious test as to how to
deal with e2-e4.}) ({Finally,} 6... Na6 7. e3 Nb4 8. Bxc4 {is sometimes played,
but white should be able to obtain opening advantage in all lines without much
trouble. It should just be noted that} Nc2+ $4 {blunders a piece due to} 9.
Qxc2 Bxc2 10. Bxf7# {This, and other sidelines on move 6, will be covered in
Chapter 5.}) 7. Nxc4 {Here we have another crossroads for black with two major
roads and one side-road. The move} Qc7 {[%cal Ge7e5] preparing central break
e7-e5, has been the most popular for the last 85 years, though it has had its
ups and downs. It has been revitalized in the beginning of this century by
Alexander Morozevich, who brought it into the spot-light with the ingenious
idea 11..g5!?} ({The main alternative} 7... Nb6 8. Ne5 a5 {has been
popularized by Ivan Sokolov around the same time as Morozevich's 7...Qc7 and
11...g5. It was taken up by leading Chinese GMs who have scored well with it.
Black does not directly attack white's center, but rather wants to create a
solid position without apparent weaknesses, similar to 6.e3 line (instead of 6.
Ne5). Having this in mind, I would recommend a modern aggresive approach with}
9. h4 $5 {This move has much more subtleties than it might seem at the first
sight and it has scored superbly over the last year or so. White has not fully
proven the advantage in other lines, such as 9.f3, 9.e3 and 9.g3, while black
has not yet proven full equality in 9.h4 either! It is analyzed in detail in
Chapter 6.}) (7... Nd5 {is another one of Morozevich's brainchilds in the
Classical Slav. While very solid, it doesn't pose white much problem in
obtaining opening advantage after} 8. f3 e5 9. e4 Nxc3 10. bxc3 {and so on. I
will explain how to exactly obtain advantage against 7...Nd5 and the harmless
7...e6 in Chapter 7.}) {The principled reaction to black's plan is of course:}
8. g3 {[%cal Gc1f4] and now} e5 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Bf4 Nfd7 11. Bg2 {brings us
to the tabiya of Classical Slav. Here Morozevich came up with fantastic} g5 $5
{This move has given white quite a few headaches over the years. However, by
now a reliable path to advantageous positions for white has been found with 12.
Ne3, which incidentally, is also the move that Garry Kasparov used to beat
Morozevich, when he faced 11...g5!? for the first time in 2001.} ({In the 20th
century,} 11... f6 {and related moves such as Be6, have been considered "a
must". However, white is able to obtain a small, but stable advantage in these
lines.} 12. O-O {The old main line 11...f6 is analyzed in Chapter 8, while the
solid, though a bit outdated alternatives are covered in Chapter 9.}) 12. Ne3 (
12. Bxe5 Nxe5 13. Qd4) ({and} 12. Nxe5 gxf4 13. Nxd7 {are the alternatives.})
12... gxf4 13. Nxf5 {[%csl Gb4,Gf5,Rf7,Rh7] We will explore this important
position in great detail in Chapter 10. Proving white's advantage is not
simple in some variations due to black's blockade on the dark squares and the
threat of serious kingside counterplay with h5-h4. Yet, it should make sense
that white's chances are better due to strong outpost on f5 and a superior
pawn structure on the kingside (which can make a difference in the endgame).
As it is, from the standpoint of opening theory the viability of Classical
Slav depends to a large degree on the evaluation of this position.} *

