1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 Bg4 {This provocative variation
captured attention of many Soviet GMs in the old time as the main alternative
to 5...Bf5. The idea of Bg4 is, apart from developing a piece, to weaken
white's control of d4 square.} ({In the variation} 5... Na6 {the knight is
obviously headed to b4 square. While this square is comfortable for the knight,
black is giving white the golden opportunity to seize the center with e2-e4.}
6. e4 Bg4 7. Bxc4 Bxf3 {Spoiling white's pawn structure justifies black's
previous play somewhat.} 8. gxf3 Nb4 ({Black can also omit playing Nb4 to
complete development quickly, as Bxa6 is not in white's plans.} 8... e6 9. O-O
Be7 10. Kh1 $1 {[%cal Gf1g1,Gg1g7] This manouevre is very important to
remember. White uses his weakness in pawn structure as a strength in attack 
(g-file).} O-O 11. Rg1 Kh8 12. f4 Nb4 13. e5 Nfd5 14. Ne4 $14 {[%csl Ge4]} f5
15. exf6 Bxf6 16. Ra3 $1 {[%cal Ga3h3]} Qe8 17. Rh3 $40 Rd8 18. Qg4 Qf7 19. Bd2
a5 20. f5 exf5 21. Qxf5 Qg8 22. Qg6 Be7 23. Rg5 {1-0 Ragger,M (2676)-David,A 
(2571)/Zillertal 2015/CBM 167 Extra}) 9. O-O e6 10. Kh1 $1 {[%cal Gf1g1] White
should not waste time on moves like Be3 - he should launch the attack as
quickly as possible.} Be7 (10... Qa5 $5 {is an interesting plan preparing long
castle!?} 11. Rg1 h6 12. Be3 O-O-O 13. Qb3 Kb8 {and here a famous chess author
and strong Israeli GM found a nice move:} 14. Be2 $1 $14 {[%csl Rc4,Gf3][%cal
Gc3b1,Gb1d2,Gd2c4] 1-0 Avrukh,B (2628)-Kogan,A (2591)/Maalot-Tarshiha 2008/CBM
122/[Avrukh,B] (44)}) 11. Rg1 O-O 12. Bh6 Ne8 13. Qd2 Kh8 14. Be3 a5 15. Rg3 $1
{[%cal Gg3h3,Ga1g1]} Qd7 16. Rag1 $14 Rd8 17. f4 g6 18. Qe2 Ng7 19. Bb3 Qe8 20.
Rh3 $40 {1-0 Van der Stricht,G (2417)-Mohandesi,S (2246)/Namur 2006/CBM 113
Extra (35)}) (5... a5 {This rare line gained some popularity lately as it
leads to standardly solid Classical Slav positions with little theory.} 6. e4
Bg4 7. Bxc4 e6 8. O-O Bb4 9. Qd3 Nbd7 (9... Bxf3 10. gxf3 Nbd7 11. f4 O-O 12.
Rd1 Nb6 13. Bb3 $14 c5 14. e5 Nfd5 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. f5 $36 {1-0 (23) Avrukh,B
(2645)-Welling,G (2364) Kemer 2007}) 10. Bf4 O-O {This solid position is
probably black's best bet in this line. However, white can obtain a small, but
long-term advantage with} 11. Ne5 $1 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gf2f3]} Nxe5 12. Bxe5 Bh5
13. f3 Nd7 14. Bg3 Qe7 15. Rfd1 Rfd8 16. Qe2 Rac8 17. Rac1 $14 {and white was
more comfortable in 1/2-1/2 Cramling,P (2491)-Brunello,S (2581)/Caleta 2012/
CBM 147 (24)}) (5... c5 {is not at all that bad, especially as a surprise
weapon. Now} 6. d5 {is principled} (6. e4 cxd4 7. Qxd4 Qxd4 8. Nxd4 e5 $1 9.
Ndb5 Na6 10. Bxc4 Bc5 11. Ke2 Be6 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. Be3 Ke7 14. f3 Bxe3 15.
Kxe3 Nd7 $1 $11 {is completely harmless. 0-1 Knott,S (2361)-Duncan,C (2324)/
West Bromwich 2004/EXT 2005 (50)}) 6... e6 (6... Bf5 $6 {prevents e2-e4, but
is inconsistent. White has a nice idea to regain the pawn:} 7. a5 $1 {[%cal
Gd1a4,Ga4c4,Re2e4]} g6 8. Qa4+ Bd7 9. Qxc4 Na6 10. e4 Nb4 11. Qb3 {This
position resembles the Russian system in Gruenfeld a lot - and this is a very
good version of it for white.} Bg7 12. Bc4 O-O 13. O-O b5 14. axb6 axb6 {1/2-1/
2 Williams,S (2267)-Duncan,C (2322)/England 2014/EXT 2015 (50)} 15. Bf4 $16) 7.
e4 exd5 8. e5 $1 {Very concrete.} (8. exd5 Bd6 9. Bxc4 O-O 10. O-O {is
possible, but much less convincing.}) 8... Nbd7 $5 {Piece sacrifice of this
type is not unseen. Black will get a chunk of pawns in the center for the
piece - enough for some compensation.} (8... d4 {is an attempt to complicate
matters even further, but white can make a counter-sacrifice!} 9. Bxc4 Ng4 10.
Qb3 Qd7 11. O-O $1 Nc6 (11... dxc3 12. Rd1 cxb2 13. Bxb2 $40 {[%csl Re8] gives
white a tremendous attack a la Evans gambit.}) 12. Ng5 {This leads to a nice
attacking position for white, as in the following game:} Ngxe5 (12... dxc3 13.
Nxf7) 13. Re1 f6 (13... Kd8 14. Bxf7 c4 15. Bxc4 Na5 16. Ne6+ Qxe6 17. Bxe6
Nxb3 18. Bxb3 dxc3 19. Rxe5 $16) 14. Bf7+ Kd8 15. Ne6+ Ke7 16. Nxc5 $18 {1-0
Nikolov,M (2549)-Duncan,C (2317)/Plovdiv 2010/CBM 139 (24)}) 9. exf6 Nxf6 {Now
white just needs to find the best places for his remaining light pieces. I
would suggest the following setup:} 10. Bg5 Be6 11. g3 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gf1g2]
Fianchetto is generally the best way to target the isolated/weak pawn on d5.}
Be7 12. Bg2 O-O 13. O-O d4 $6 {The practical problem of such clustered pawns
is that they are the strongest in their current state - as soon as one of them
moves forward, they lose their potential energy. In this case, c4 pawn loses
protection.} (13... h6 $142 14. Bf4 $14) 14. Ne2 h6 {1-0 Potpara,N (2157)
-Schreiner,P (2257)/Batumi 2010/CBM 138 Extra (37)} 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Nf4 $16 {
[%csl Rc4]}) ({Among many minor lines, let us mention Morozevich's ambitious,
although probably incorrect delayed Albin counter-gambit:} 5... e5 6. Nxe5 Bb4
7. e3 Be6 8. Be2 $1 ({Of course, not} 8. Bxc4 Bxc4 9. Nxc4 Qd5 $1 $132 {[%csl
Rc4,Rg2][%cal Gd5c4,Gd5g2]}) 8... c5 (8... Ne4 9. Bd2 Nd6 10. Ne4 $1 Nxe4 11.
Bxb4 c5 12. Bc3 $16 {[%csl Rc4] 1-0 Bacrot,E (2618)-Morozevich,A (2745)/Cannes
2001/CBM 082 (53)}) 9. O-O cxd4 10. exd4 Nc6 11. Bxc4 Bxc4 12. Nxc4 {[%csl Gd5]
White's up a clear pawn, though black can put up serious resistance with
blockade on d5.} O-O 13. Be3 Rc8 14. Qb3 Ng4 15. Rad1 Bxc3 16. Qxc3 Qd5 17. b3
Rcd8 18. f3 Nf6 19. Bf2 $16 {1/2-1/2 Alekseev,E (2616)-Yevseev,D (2580)/St
Petersburg 2004/CBM 102 (30)}) {Unsurprisinlgy, white's most common answer is}
6. Ne5 Bh5 {Here white has a plenty of options, but I would recommend the most
principled one and the one most consistent with other lines we will examine
against the Classical Slav:} 7. f3 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gg2g4] This move goes
hand-in-hand with knight jump to e5 and serves the purpose of fortifying
white's center. As we will see, in some lines this move also supports
dangerous g2-g4 push now that black bishop is on h5.} Nfd7 {Challenging white
knight immediately is the most principled continuation for black.} ({The
alternative} 7... e6 {is a bit slow and allows} 8. g4 {with the idea to trap
the bishop with h4-h5.} {Now the most testing move is piece sacrifice:} Nfd7 ({
In case of} 8... Bg6 9. h4 {[%csl Rg6] black's dark-squared bishop is in
trouble and he can either try to muddy the water with} c5 ({or accept a pretty
miserable pawn structure after} 9... h6 10. Nxg6 fxg6 {[%csl Re6,Rg6]} 11. e4
c5 {1-0 Sosonko,G (2575)-Timman,J (2605)/Tilburg 1983/MCD (38)} 12. d5 $1 exd5
13. e5 $16) 10. h5 Bd3 $5 {Here, the new strong move} 11. d5 $1 $146 {gives
white excellent chances in the complications.} (11. exd3 cxd4 {was far less
clear in 1-0 (34) Moiseenko,A (2711)-Ponkratov,P (2605) Khanty-Mansiysk 2013.})
{For example:} 11... Bd6 12. f4 Be4 13. dxe6 $1 Bxh1 14. Nxf7 Nc6 15. Nxd8 Rxd8
16. g5 $18) ({Another knight jump} 8... Nd5 {should be answered with energetic}
9. e4 $1 (9. gxh5 $2 {[%csl Rd4]} Qh4+ 10. Kd2 Qxd4+ {is black's idea.}) 9...
Qh4+ 10. Ke2 {[%csl Ge2] White should not fear walking his king in many lines
of Classical Slav, as it is often the only way to keep the central domination.
Black does not have enough pieces to endanger it anyway.} Nxc3+ 11. bxc3 Bg6
12. Bf4 Qd8 13. Qb1 b6 14. Kf2 Bd6 15. Bxc4 $16 {Black has saved his bishop,
but his position was quite poor in 1-0 Zhao,X (2423)-Wang,Y (2390)/Wuxi 2006/
CBM 113 Extra (30)}) 9. Nxd7 Qh4+ 10. Kd2 {[%cal Gd2c2,Gc2b1]} Nxd7 11. gxh5
Nc5 $1 {This is black's tricky idea.} (11... Qxd4+ 12. Kc2 $16) 12. Kc2 Nb3 13.
Kb1 $1 {But white king marched to queenside safety! White just needs to be
careful to avoid tricks and he should be on his way to a large advantage, as
the following games show:} O-O-O 14. e3 e5 (14... Nxa1 15. Kxa1 Bb4 16. Bxc4 e5
17. Qb3 Bxc3 18. bxc3 $18 {1-0 Shulman,Y (2591)-Jacobs,B/Stillwater 2002/CBM
090 Extra (25)}) 15. Bxc4 Nxa1 16. Bxf7 $1 Qf6 17. Ba2 exd4 18. exd4 Rxd4 19.
Qe2 Bb4 {1/2-1/2 Naumann,A (2524)-Gozzoli,Y (2431)/Pula 2003/CBM 094 Extra (32)
} 20. Ne4 Qe5 21. Kxa1 $18) 8. Nxc4 e5 {Bronstein's idea.} (8... Qc7 {was
played by GM Ulibin in a few games with reasonable success, until the
following game:} 9. e4 f6 10. d5 $1 Bf7 11. Be3 Na6 12. Rc1 e5 13. dxc6 bxc6
14. Nxe5 $14 {[%csl Ra6] winning a pawn for which black can not show enough
compensation.} fxe5 15. Bxa6 Bc5 16. Bxc5 Nxc5 17. Nd5 $1 cxd5 18. Bb5+ Ke7 19.
b4 a6 20. Be2 $16 {1-0 Bellon Lopez,J (2428)-Ulibin,M (2581)/Stockholm 2003/
CBM 091 Extra (61)}) 9. e4 {[%csl Rh5] Accepting the pawn was unnecessarily
risky for white. With 9.e4, we play for simple advantages - the strong center
and locked out Bh5.} Qh4+ $5 {The sharpest move.} ({Normal developing moves
such as Bb4 or f6 lead to solid positions that are, however, always better for
white.} 9... Bb4 10. dxe5 O-O 11. Be3 (11. Bf4 $14 {holding onto the pawn is
possible, too.}) 11... Qe7 12. Be2 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 14. O-O Qe7 15. a5 Nd7
16. Qb3 Bc5 17. Bxc5 Nxc5 18. Qc4 Rad8 19. Rfd1 $14 {[%csl Rh5] 1-0 Grischuk,A
(2717)-Korotylev,A (2609)/Moscow 2006/EXT 2007 (51)}) 10. g3 Qf6 {[%csl Rf3]
[%cal Gf6f3]} 11. dxe5 Qxf3 {Softening up the kingside was the idea behind Qh4
check, so this double-edged move is principled.} ({It wouldn't make much sense
then to play} 11... Nxe5 $2 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 13. g4 Bg6 14. f4 {[%csl Rg6]} Qe7
15. f5 Qh4+ 16. Kd2 Nd7 17. Kc2 O-O-O 18. Qe2 Ne5 19. Bf4 $18 {It is funny how
white does not have to rush to take the bishop at all and can simply finish
development instead. 1-0 Leitao,R (2629)-Cubas,J (2463)/Santos 2010/CBM 137
Extra (24)}) 12. Nd6+ $1 {This natural move implies a rook sacrifice.} Ke7 {
The best answer.} ({Accepting the rook sacrifice with} 12... Bxd6 13. Qxd6 Qxh1
$6 {leaves black king in a precarious situation.} 14. Bg5 {[%csl Re8]} f6 15.
exf6 gxf6 16. Bxf6 Nxf6 17. Qe6+ $1 Kf8 18. Qxf6+ Kg8 19. Qd8+ Kf7 20. Qxh8 $18
{1-0 Nikolaidis,I (2520)-Fontaine,R (2537)/Cannes 2005/CBM 105 Extra (30)}) ({
The other king move} 12... Kd8 {leaves f7 undefended after the queen exchange:}
13. Qxf3 Bxf3 14. Nxf7+ Ke8 {and now the practice has proved that} 15. e6 $1 {
yields white a huge advantage:} Nc5 (15... Bxh1 $2 16. exd7+ Nxd7 17. Nxh8 $18)
16. Rg1 Nb3 (16... Nxe6 17. Nxh8 Bc5 18. Bc4 $1 Bxg1 19. Bxe6 Ke7 20. Bc8 a5
21. Bg5+ Kf8 22. Kd2 {1-0 Hummel,P (2330)-Filipovich,D (2236)/North Bay 1999/
EXT 2000}) 17. Bc4 Nxa1 18. Nxh8 Nc2+ 19. Kd2 Nd4 20. Kd3 $16 {1-0 Kuligin,E 
(2336)-Dashevsky,S (2268)/Nizhnij Tagil 2007/EXT 2009 (41)}) {In this
double-edged position, the best move is:} 13. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Gd6,Re7][%cal
Gf4e5]} Qxd1+ (13... h6 {[%cal Gg7g5] also makes sense, as in 1-0 Szabo,B 
(2333)-Kersic,M (2168)/Pula 2012/CBM 148 Extra} {Here white can improve on the
aforementioned game with} 14. Qb3 $1 $146 Nc5 (14... Qxh1 15. Qxb7 g5 16. Qc8
$1 f6 17. g4 Bg6 18. O-O-O $18) 15. Qc4 Qxh1 16. Qxc5 Nd7 17. Qb4 Rb8 18. Qd4
$40 Kd8 19. Nxf7+ $3 Bxf7 20. O-O-O Be6 21. Bc4 Bc5 22. Qd3 $18) (13... Qxh1
14. Qxh5 $18) 14. Nxd1 $14 {[%csl Ra8,Rb8,Gd6,Rf8,Rh5,Rh8] The queenless
middlegame is definitely in white's favor due to the disarray among black
forces. In the only game played in this position black quickly went astray:}
Bf3 $2 15. Rg1 h6 16. Ne3 $18 {and white got an overwhelming position in
Kremenetsky,A-Yanovsky,S, Moscow 1988.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2016.02.23"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Classical Slav"]
[Black "CHAPTER 2: 5...e6"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D16"]
[Annotator "GM Kuljasevic, Davorin"]
[PlyCount "43"]
[EventDate "2006.03.11"]
[SourceDate "2016.01.25"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 e6 {[%cal Gc6c5,Yf8b4] This
hybrid variation was first played in 1930-is, but was left for dead after
Alexander Alekhine won a few games against it in a very convincing fashion. It
was revived by Vladimir Kramnik's analysis team for the World Championship
match against Leko in 2004, where Kramnik scored an effortless draw with black.
Soon thereafter, it began gaining popularity among strong players as a very
solid weapon. Alekhine considered the move dubious due to 6.e4, but things are
not so simple today as they were in 1935. The main move these days is
apparently modest:} 6. e3 ({According to Alekhine, the principled reaction is} 
6. e4 Bb4 7. e5 Nd5 8. Bd2 {though the position after} b5 9. axb5 (9. h4 $5 {
[%csl Rg7][%cal Gh1h3,Gh3g3] is an interesting idea of ever-creative
Morozevich.}) 9... Bxc3 10. bxc3 cxb5 11. Ng5 $44 {[%csl Yb7,Gc5,Yd5,Gd6][%cal
Gg5e4,Gd1h5,Gc8b7] is objectively complicated. White has a sufficient
compensation for the pawn in the view of kingside attack and dark-square
control, but black has a strong light-squared blockade and a powerful knight
on d5. The sheer amount of complicated variations one has to remember and the
riskiness of such positions make me very hesitant to recommend this variation
as a part of steady repertoire to anyone, even a Grandmaster! I have therefore
chosen a more orthodox line 6.e3 that is, despite humble appearances, not
without attacking potential.}) 6... c5 {Black is aiming for a Queen's gambit
declined position where white has played a4.} 7. Bxc4 Nc6 (7... cxd4 8. exd4
Be7 ({or} 8... Nc6 9. O-O Be7 10. Qe2) 9. O-O O-O 10. Qe2 Nc6 11. Rd1 {is
basically just a transposition.}) 8. O-O Be7 9. Qe2 $1 {Leaving the pawn on d4
without protection, but this is a poisoned pawn.} cxd4 ({Black could also try
to avoid taking on d4} 9... O-O 10. Rd1 Qb6 (10... Qc7 {was not tried too
often, but seems quite solid. White can get a small advantage by playing simply
} 11. e4 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 cxd4 13. Rxd4 e5 (13... Bc5 14. Rd1 $14 {[%cal Ge4e5]})
14. Rd1 $14 {[%csl Gd5]}) 11. d5 exd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Nb4 14. Bc4 Bf6
15. e4 Be6 16. e5 Be7 17. Bg5 $14 {1-0 Ladva,O (2353)-Fedoseev,V (2641)/Riga
2014/CBM 159 Extra (41)}) 10. exd4 O-O ({Black does not have a6 included, as
in a similar position from QGA, therefore taking on d4 is a mistake:} 10...
Nxd4 $2 11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. Nb5 $1 {[%csl Gb5]} Qd8 13. Bf4 O-O 14. Nc7 Rb8 15.
Rfd1 Bd7 16. Nxe6 $1 $18 fxe6 17. Bxe6+ Kh8 18. Bxd7 Nxd7 19. Bxb8 Bc5 20. Bg3
{1-0 Kunin,V (2535)-Pfrommer,C (2326)/Frankfurt 2010/EXT 2012}) 11. Rd1 {[%csl
Ga7,Rc8,Gd5] And here we are - we reached the tabiya of 5...e6 6.e3. Black is
a tempo down compared to QGA (he played 2 moves with c-pawn instead of one),
so the only difference is that his pawn is on a7, rather than on a6. There has
been a debate on whether this detail makes a substantial difference or not and
the conclusion is that it is not of huge importance. There are some nuances
that favor white, but basically black is very solid regardless of the position
of a-pawn.  Since this is an isolated queen's pawn position, let us quickly
repeat some ground rules about such positions. Firstly, the square in front of
the isolated pawn (d5) is critical and black should try to have it under
control. Secondly, black can equalize only if he is able to develop his
light-squared bishop comfortably, ideally via b6, Bb7. Thirdly, white should
not trade pieces unless it brings him a certain positional benefit. Instead,
he should try to either orchestrate a kingside attack or use his space
advantage and centralization for other purposes.  Having all this in mind, let
us proceed. Black has 2 main moves in this position: Nb4 and Nd5, both
increasing control over d5 square.} Nb4 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gb4d5] The most
natural move, using the Achilles heel of white's position - the b4 square - to
increase control over d5.} (11... Nd5 {the idea of this move is to avoid Bg5
which can happen in case of 12...Nb4. Here white has a wide choice of options.
The one I would propose is} 12. Bd2 {- a natural developing move, which will
also keep an eye on b4 knight in some variations.} (12. Bb3 $5 {is another
good move worth investigating.}) 12... Ncb4 ({If black tries to complete
development with} 12... b6 {white should change the character of position with}
13. Nxd5 $1 exd5 14. Bb5 $14 {and in such a symmetrical structure, as we know
from famous game between Botvinnik and Alekhine, the weakness of c6 square is
a long-term structural weakness for black.}) 13. a5 $1 {[%cal Rb7b6,Ga5b6]
This move stops black from developing his bishop to b7, so he needs to take
another, less preferred route:} Bd7 14. Nxd5 {White wanted to play Ne5 without
having to worry about Nc2 with double attack on a1 and d4, thus this exchange.}
Nxd5 ({We can see usefulness of Bd2 in the following line:} 14... exd5 15. Bxb4
$1 Bxb4 16. Bxd5 $16) 15. Ne5 {[%csl Ge5] We reached the main position of the
12.Bd2 line. Here the games branch:} Rc8 {should be the best move, in my
opinion.} (15... Be8 {[%csl Ge8,Rf8][%cal Gd8d5] was played by Korobov against
Kramnik in the World Cup. Black removes the bishop from d-file, but also clogs
Rf8. Kramnik's subsequent play is instructive:} 16. Qf3 {[%cal Gf3d5]} f6 {
[%csl Re6][%cal Ge8f7] A sensible plan, though e6 will need some extra care
from now on.} 17. Nd3 Bf7 18. Qg4 {[%cal Gg4e6,Gg4g7]} Kh8 19. Nc5 $1 $14 {
[%csl Rb7,Gc5,Re6]} Bxc5 20. dxc5 Qc7 21. a6 bxa6 22. b4 Rfd8 23. Rxa6 h5 24.
Qf3 $16 {and he achieved a strategically winning position in 1-0 (51) Kramnik,
V (2784)-Korobov,A (2720) Tromso NOR 2013}) ({was tried by GM Postny against
yours truly, but bishop is loose here.} 15... Bc6 16. a6 {[%csl Rc6][%cal
Ge5c6]} Nf6 {[%cal Gc6d5]} (16... Bd6 $14 {[%cal Gd6e5] with the idea to get
rid of the knight, was more solid.}) 17. Bf4 ({Here white had an unexpectedly
strong resource:} 17. b4 $1 $16 {and black can not untangle with} Bd5 18. Bxd5
Qxd5 {because of} 19. Ra5 $1 $18 {[%csl Rb7]}) 17... Bd5 18. b3 bxa6 19. Rxa6
Bb7 20. Nc6 Qd7 21. Nxe7+ Qxe7 22. Ra5 $14 {[%csl Ra7,Gc4,Gf4] was slightly
better for white in 1/2 (26) Kuljasevic,D (2577)-Postny,E (2628) Trieste 2013})
(15... a6 {has not been tried, but black usually does well without this move.
White can continue, for example:} 16. Qd3 Rc8 ({one drawback of a6 is that} 
16... Bc6 {does not work due to} 17. Nxc6 bxc6 18. Bxa6) 17. Qb3 {[%csl Gb7]
[%cal Gc4d5,Gb3b7]} Bc6 18. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Rc6,Ge5] and black is still
facing difficulties.}) 16. a6 {It is also possible to do without this move,
but let us see the game:} b6 (16... bxa6 $2 {would not make any sense here} 17.
Rxa6 $16 {[%csl Ra7][%cal Gd2a5]}) 17. Rdc1 {looks artificial. Not sure why
the other rook is necessary on a1.} ({Why not simply:} 17. Rac1 Bd6 18. Qf3 $14
{[%cal Gf3h3,Gc4d3]} ({or} 18. Qg4 {as in the game.})) 17... Bd6 18. Qg4 Bxe5
19. dxe5 f5 $1 20. exf6 ({The last chance to claim the advantage was} 20. Qd4
Bc6 21. Bb4 $1 {the bishop is taboo} Re8 (21... Nxb4 $4 22. Bxe6+ Kh8 23. Qxb4
$18) 22. Bd6 $14 {[%csl Ra7,Gd6] black has yet to equalize.}) 20... Qxf6 21.
Rf1 Nf4 22. Rac1 b5 23. Bxf4 Rxc4 24. Rxc4 bxc4 25. Bd6 Rc8 26. Re1 c3 27. bxc3
Qxc3 $11 {1/2-1/2 Vidit,S (2602)-Barbosa,O (2564)/Kolkata 2014/CBM 159 Extra 
(39)}) (11... Bd7 $6 {and even more so 11...b6? are simply wrong because they
leave d5 undefended, so white has a thematic break} 12. d5 $1 exd5 13. Nxd5
Nxd5 14. Bxd5 $14 {[%csl Gd5]} Bf6 15. Bf4 Rc8 16. Be4 Re8 17. Ra3 $1 {[%cal
Ga3e3]} g6 18. Re3 $14 {[%cal Gd1d8,Gf4b8,Ge3e8] black is under big pressure.})
12. Bg5 {This natural move prevents black from developing his light-squared
bishop for the time being because of d4-d5! break.} h6 ({And while} 12... b6 $2
{would be fatal:} 13. d5 $1 Nbxd5 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Bxd5 $18 {
[%cal Gd5a8,Gd5f7]}) (12... Bd7 {leads to a very unpleasant endgame after} 13.
d5 $1 exd5 14. Nxd5 Nbxd5 (14... Nfxd5 $2 {is even worse due to} 15. Bxe7 Qxe7
(15... Nxe7 16. Ne5 $1 $16) 16. Qxe7 Nxe7 17. Rxd7 $18 {1-0 Malakhatko,V (2596)
-Werner,D (2346)/Germany 2007/CBM 123 (48)}) 15. Bxd5 Nxd5 16. Rxd5 Bxg5 17.
Nxg5 {[%csl Rd7,Rh7][%cal Ge2d3]} h6 18. Qd2 $1 hxg5 19. Rxd7 $16 {[%csl Gd7,
Rg5][%cal Gd7a7,Gd7g7] White has more chances to win than black has for a draw.
} Qf6 (19... Qb6 20. a5 Qb3 21. Ra3 Qe6 22. Re3 Qf5 23. Rd5 Qf6 24. Rf3 Qe7 25.
h3 Rad8 26. Qxg5 Qxg5 27. Rxg5 $16 {1/2-1/2 Harutyunian,T (2334)-Wagner,D 
(2456)/Maribor 2012/EXT 2013 (59)}) 20. Rd1 (20. Rxb7 Rab8 21. Qb4 a5 22. Qb5
Rxb7 23. Qxb7 Rd8 24. Rf1 Qe5 25. b3 g6 26. Qf3 Rd2 27. g3 Rb2 28. Rd1 $18 {
1-0 Rodshtein,M (2660)-Duda,J (2591)/Jerusalem 2015/CBM 166 (31)}) 20... b6 (
20... Rfe8 21. Rxb7 Rad8 22. Rd7 Rxd7 23. Qxd7 Rb8 24. Qxa7 Rxb2 25. h3 Ra2 26.
Qb8+ {was another one of Kramnik's convincing victories in this line: 1-0 (26)
Kramnik,V (2784)-Wang Hao (2752) Dortmund GER 2013}) 21. Rd6 Qf5 22. Rd5 Qe4 {
1-0 Palac,M (2561)-Van Foreest,J (2284)/Schwarzach 2013/CBM 156 Extra (41)} 23.
b4 $16) ({Then there is the idea to trade some pieces with} 12... Nfd5 {Here
white keeps the advantage with} 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Bxg5 15. Be4 $1 {[%cal
Ge4h7,Ge4a8]} Bf6 16. Ne5 $14 {[%csl Rc8,Ge4,Ge5] since black will not have an
easy time completing his queenside development.}) ({The other knight move to d5
} 12... Nbd5 {looks natural, but almost never solves black's problems in IQP:}
13. Ne5 Bd7 $6 {This is either a blunder or an overly optimistic pawn
sacrifice.} ({Black should trade the knight, transforming the pawn structure} 
13... Nxc3 14. bxc3 Nd5 15. Bd2 $36 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4][%cal Rc4d3,Rc3c4] which
obviously favors white.}) 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 (14... exd5 15. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 16. Bxd5
$16 {also wins a pawn.}) 15. Bxd5 Bxg5 16. Bxb7 Rb8 17. Be4 $16 {without
compensation for the pawn in 1/2 (32) Kunin,V (2538)-Teske,H (2493) Bad
Woerishofen GER 2008}) ({Black can prepare Bd7 with} 12... Re8 {[%cal Ge8e2]
when white continues} 13. Ne5 Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6,Ga8c8] Black is planning Rc8
and Bc6 after which he would have no problems whatsoever.} ({If} 13... Nfd5 {
white should of course avoid exchanges:} 14. Bd2 b6 ({Black may want to remove
the dominant knight} 14... f6 {but white has} 15. Nd3 $1 {inviting black to
take the central pawn} Nc2 16. Rac1 Nxd4 17. Qg4 Nc6 18. Nf4 $36 {[%csl Ra8,
Gc4,Rc8,Rd8,Re6,Gf4,Gg4][%cal Gd1d8] with great piece play, which seems to be
too much to handle for black who is undeveloped.}) 15. Qh5 $1 {[%csl Rf7]} Rf8
16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Nc6 {Showing why b6 was maybe not such a good idea.} Qe8 18.
Bxd5 exd5 19. Nxe7+ Qxe7 20. Qxd5 Bb7 21. Qe5 $14 {white won a pawn and
tortured black for another 30 moves until his defenses broke down in 1-0
Prohaszka,P (2567)-Sumets,A (2577)/Zug 2013/CBM 156 Extra (54)}) {Fortunately
white has the antidote:} 14. Bf4 $1 $146 {It is important to remove the bishop
from d8-h4 diagonal to make d4-d5 work. Now neither Rc8 nor Bc6 work due to
tactical reasons. Black is still struggling to equalize.} ({White got nothing
after} 14. Bb3 Rc8 15. Qf3 Bc6 16. Nxc6 bxc6 $11 17. a5 {1/2-1/2 Eljanov,P 
(2724)-Svidler,P (2730)/Olginka 2011/CBM 142}) 14... Rc8 (14... Bc6 $2 {[%csl
Re6]} 15. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 16. Qxe6+ $18) 15. d5 $1 exd5 16. Nxd5 Nbxd5 17. Bxd5
Nxd5 18. Rxd5 Bf6 19. Qd3 Bxe5 20. Bxe5 $16) 13. Bxf6 $1 {The most concrete
approach. White is not wasting any time.} Bxf6 14. Ne4 {[%cal Ge4f6]} b6 {
Black wants to finish development as quickly as possible. There are, of course,
alternatives:} ({1)} 14... Be7 15. Ne5 {[%csl Gc4,Ge4,Ge5] already looks
dangerous, so black should trade at least one knight.} Nc6 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. a5
Qc7 18. Qh5 Rd8 19. Qe5 Qb8 20. b3 Bb4 21. a6 Kf8 22. Qh5 $36 {[%csl Ra8,Rb8,
Rc8,Rd8,Rf8] Black is out of major weaknesses, but his pieces are very passive.
} Qf4 23. Qe2 Rb8 24. Rd3 Kg8 25. Rad1 Rb6 26. Rf3 $14 {after a lot of
maneouvering, white eventually found a way to break into black's position in
1-0 Van Wely,L (2654)-Van Foreest,J (2519)/Vlissingen 2015/CBM 167 Extra (44)})
({2)} 14... Nd5 15. Ne5 Be7 16. Nc3 $1 {[%csl Gd5]} Bb4 (16... Nxc3 17. bxc3
Qc7 18. Qe4 Bf6 19. Bd3 {is already pleasant for white.} g6 20. Qf4 Bg5 21. Qg3
Bd7 22. h4 $36 {1/2-1/2 Postny,E (2652)-Yilmaz,M (2580)/Germany 2015/CBM 165 
(42)}) 17. Qf3 Bxc3 18. bxc3 Qd6 19. Bb3 Rb8 20. Rd3 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Gd3h3]
Rook lift to the 3rd rank is always welcome in the isolated queen's pawn
positions.} b6 21. Qg4 f5 22. Qh4 Bb7 23. Rg3 $40 {1-0 Gupta,A (2593)-Danin,A 
(2589)/Bad Wiessee 2013/EXT 2014 (36)}) 15. Ne5 Bb7 {With this move black
finishes development, but runs into some new problems.} (15... Bh4 $5 {looks a
bit radical, but avoids Nxf6 in case of Bb7. Here the rook lift} 16. Ra3 Bb7
17. Rh3 {looks quite promising. Two games were played from this position:} Nd5
(17... Bd5 18. Nc3 Bxc4 19. Qxc4 Be7 20. Qe2 Rc8 21. Qg4 $36 {with kingside
initiative for white. I give the remainder of the game because it is always
instructive to see how strong players play out typical positions.} Kh7 22. Rg3
Bf6 23. Ne4 Rc7 24. h4 Qe7 25. Kh2 Nd5 26. Nxf6+ Qxf6 27. Rdd3 Ne7 28. Rgf3 Nf5
29. g3 Kg8 30. Qf4 Rd8 31. d5 Rc2 32. Nxf7 Rf8 33. dxe6 Rc5 34. b4 {1-0
Tomashevsky,E (2743)-Mchedlishvili,M (2618)/Reykjavik ISL 2015/The Week in
Chess 1098}) 18. Qg4 Bg5 19. Rf3 ({In the following game, white traded a lot
of pieces - something that can be good only for black.} 19. Nxg5 $6 Qxg5 20.
Qxg5 hxg5 $15 {1/2-1/2 Ikonnikov,V (2527)-Van Foreest,J (2514)/Dieren 2015/CBM
167 Extra (77)}) 19... Nf6 20. Nxf6+ Bxf6 21. Rh3 $36 {White has good
attacking prospects. If black decides to make his life easier by trading off
some pieces} Bxe5 22. dxe5 Qg5 23. Qxg5 hxg5 {white still keeps an edge in the
endgame:} 24. Rhd3 $14 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gd3d8]}) 16. Nxf6+ $1 Qxf6 17. Nd7 Qg6
(17... Qg5 18. f4 $1 Qxf4 19. Nxf8 Rxf8 20. a5 $14) 18. d5 $1 {This is the
point.} Rfe8 (18... exd5 $6 {is just losing an exchange for little
compensation.} 19. Nxf8 Rxf8 20. Bd3 Qd6 21. Qf3 a5 22. Bb5 Bc6 23. Bxc6 Qxc6
24. Qf4 Qg6 25. Ra3 Qc2 26. Qd4 $16 {0-1 (45) Edouard,R (2686)-Ernst,S (2556)
Wijk aan Zee NED 2013}) 19. Ne5 Qg5 {was seen in 1/2-1/2 Bacrot,E (2711)
-Kempinski,R (2625)/Jerusalem 2015/CBM 166} {Here simply} 20. Nf3 Qf6 21. dxe6
fxe6 22. Ne5 $14 {[%csl Gc4,Ge5,Re6,Rg8] gave white a small, but stable
advantage.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2016.02.23"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Classical Slav"]
[Black "CHAPTER 3: 6...e6 7.f3 c5"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D17"]
[Annotator "GM Kuljasevic, Davorin"]
[PlyCount "49"]
[EventDate "2006.03.11"]
[SourceDate "2016.01.25"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 Bf5 6. Ne5 e6 7. f3 c5 {[%csl
Rd4][%cal Gc5d4,Ge2e4] In different positions where white prepares e2-e4 with
f2-f3, black's best reaction is to attack the other central pawn (d4) with c5
break. Black is using the same logic here.} 8. e4 Bg6 {This modest
continuation was tested in Wch matches between Topalov and Kramnik (2006) and
Topalov and Anand (2010). Black does not even pretend to get anything more
than a draw in this line (perfect for Wch matches), so white should thread
carefully if he wants to get the full point.} ({Strangely enough, black has a
very sharp alternative on the very same move:} 8... cxd4 9. exf5 Bb4 {[%cal
Gb4e1]} ({Black have also tried} 9... Nc6 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. fxe6 fxe6 {playing
for compensation as white is behind in development.} {Now the most promising
seems to be returning the piece with:} 12. Qe2 $1 dxc3 13. Qxe6+ Qe7 14. Bxc4
Qxe6+ 15. Bxe6 $14 {[%csl Gc1,Ge6] This endgame is reached by force. White's
bishop pair on the open board is a very important factor. He only needs to
complete development.} cxb2 ({If} 15... Bb4 {then even} 16. O-O $1 {is possible
} Ke7 17. Bc4 cxb2 18. Bxb2 $14 {[%csl Gb2,Gc4,Yc6,Rg7,Rh7][%cal Gb2g7,Gc4g8]
1/2-1/2 Alterman,B (2585)-Huzman,A (2570)/Haifa 1996/CBM 054/[Alterman,B] (44)
White's advantage is not big, but is very stable due to the bishop pair,
blocked c-pawn and the potential to attack black kingside pawns. With good
endgame technique, he should be able to pose serious practical problems for
black.}) 16. Bxb2 Bb4+ 17. Ke2 Ke7 18. Bc4 Nd5 {This is probably necessary,
otherwise the bishops are too strong.} ({as in the following game:} 18... Rhd8
19. Rhd1 Rab8 20. g3 h5 21. Rd4 Ba5 22. Ba3+ Ke8 23. Rad1 $16 {[%csl Ga3,Gc4]
[%cal Ga3f8,Gc4g8] (41) 1-0 Topalov,V (2700)-Gelfand,B (2700)/Dos Hermanas
1996/CBM 053 (41)}) 19. Bxd5 $6 {I do not agree with this decision.} (19. Rac1
$142 $14 {[%cal Gh1d1,Ge2f2] makes more sense, keeping pressure on black's
position.}) 19... cxd5 20. Rhc1 Bd6 21. g3 Rhe8 22. Kd3 $14 {White still has a
miniscule advantage in the endgame, but black should have very good drawing
chances.} g5 23. Bd4 Kd7 $2 (23... Rf8 $14) 24. Rab1 Reb8 25. Rxb8 Rxb8 26.
Bxa7 Ra8 27. Be3 $16 {1-0 Stefansson,H (2535)-Gretarsson,H (2480)/Munkebo 1998/
CBM 067/[Huebner,R] (43)}) 10. Bxc4 $1 {This active move forces favorable
complications for white.} dxc3 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. Nxf7+ $1 {Extremely sharp,
but it works!} Ke8 (12... Ke7 13. bxc3 Bxc3+ 14. Ke2 {may lead to
transposition to the main line after Kxf7. But if black gets greedy with} Bxa1
$2 {white's attack after} 15. fxe6 $18 {[%cal Gc1a3] is even stronger with
black king on e7, as Ba3 comes with check.}) 13. bxc3 Bxc3+ 14. Ke2 $40 Kxf7 {
White is obviously sacrificing everything to hunt down black king, so
eliminating a dangerous knight is a lesser evil} ({compared to the greedy} 
14... Bxa1 {Now white doesn't take the rook, but rather plays for attack with}
15. fxe6 $1 $40 Rg8 16. Ba3 {[%csl Ga3,Ra8,Gc4,Ge6,Re8,Gf7,Rg8] A fascinating
concept. White is a rook down, yet black is struggling to hold the position
together.} Bd4 17. Rb1 $1 {Threats are coming from all sides.} b6 {This
weakens a4-e8 diagonal, but the alternative Bb6 isn't any better.} (17... Bb6
18. Nd6+ Kd8 19. e7+ $1 Kxe7 20. Ne4+ Kd8 21. Nxf6 gxf6 (21... Rh8 $2 22. Rd1+
Kc8 23. Be6+ Kc7 24. Nd5+ $18) 22. Bxg8 $18) 18. Bb5+ Nbd7 19. Bc6 Rc8 20. Nd6+
$18 {was decisive in the game 1-0 Alekseev,E (2689)-Wang,Y (2696)/Nizhnij
Novgorod 2007/CBM 120/[Stohl,I] (45)}) 15. fxe6+ Ke8 (15... Ke7 16. Ba3+ Kd8
17. Rhd1+ Kc8 18. Rac1 Be5 19. Bb5+ Nc6 20. Bxc6 bxc6 21. Rxc6+ Kb7 22. Rc5 Bc7
23. Rb1+ Bb6 24. a5 $18 {1-0 Zhou,J (2652)-Lin,C (2448)/Hefei 2010/CBM 136
Extra (38)}) 16. Rb1 $1 {We have seen a similar idea in the game Alekseev -
Wang Yue. Black must make some sort of a concession, which helps white to
develop his attack.} Nc6 (16... b6 $2 17. Ba3 $18 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gc4b5]}) 17.
Rxb7 a6 18. Ba3 $40 {[%csl Ga3,Gc4,Re8][%cal Gb7g7] White can have fun now.}
Ng8 (18... Be5 19. Rd1 $18) 19. Rhb1 Be5 20. g3 Na5 21. Rf7 Nf6 22. Ba2 $18 {
White probably messed up big time not to win this overwhelming position in 1/
2-1/2 Kragelj,I (2219)-Hansen,V (2123)/Trieste 2011/CBM 144 Extra (52)}) 9. Be3
cxd4 10. Qxd4 Qxd4 11. Bxd4 {[%csl Rg6] Black's idea with 7...c5 an 8...Bg6
was to enter this passive, but solid endgame. White will obviously regain the
pawn on c4, which leaves us with an almost symmetrical pawn structure where a
chronic problem for black is his misplaced light-squared bishop. But, if black
manages to bring this bishop into the game in time, he is very likely to
equalize the game (which is why this variation was appealing to World
championship contenders in the first place).} Nfd7 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gf6f5] The
most logical way to challenge the knight on e5 as it also gives black the
opportunity to later bring his bishop into to game either via 1) f7-f6, Bf7
and e5 (or Be8-c6) or 2) f7-f5, exf5, Bxf5.} (11... Nc6 {was played by the
ex-World champion and a Slav expert, Vassily Smyslov, but is less appealing as
white can at least get a structural advantage with} 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Bxc4 {
[%csl Ra7,Rc6]} Nd7 14. Ke2 e5 15. Be3 a5 16. Rhd1 Rb8 17. Rd2 Bb4 18. Rad1 Nf6
19. Rc2 $14 {[%csl Rg6] 1-0 Cramling,P-Smyslov,V/Roquebrune 1998/CBM 67 noVC 
(70)  In this game we can clearly see how black light-squared bishop is out of
play.}) 12. Nxd7 ({In the light of discussion on bad position of light squared
bishop, it would make no sense to "win the bishop pair" with} 12. Nxg6 $6 hxg6
13. Bxc4 Nc6 $11) 12... Nxd7 13. Bxc4 {This is the starting position of the "1.
d4 Berlin endgame" (due to its drawish tendencies). Black has two choices: 1)}
Rc8 {Immediately attacking the bishop, but also allowing Bb5.} ({2)} 13... a6 {
[%csl Gb5] This move stops Bb5, but wastes some time.} 14. Rc1 Rg8 {[%csl Rg7]
[%cal Gf8c5] The fact that black has to play such move to complete his
development speaks about the passivity of his position. Yet, it remains very
solid and if white does not play energetically enough, black will eventually
equalize.} ({If} 14... Rc8 {white can employ a nice knight maneouvre:} 15. Ne2
$1 Rg8 16. h4 h6 17. Kf2 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Gh1c1,Gc4e6] white already has some
tactical ideas like Bxe6.} Rc6 18. b4 $1 $16 {An idea worth remembering.} Kd8 (
18... Bxb4 19. Bxa6 $1 Rxa6 20. Rc8+ Ke7 21. Rxg8 {is the trick!}) (18... e5
19. Be3 Bxb4 20. Bxa6 $1 $18 {1-0 Gyimesi,Z (2600)-Bogosavljevic,B (2531)/
Bihac 2010/CBM 136 Extra (46)}) 19. h5 Bh7 20. b5 axb5 21. Bxb5 Rxc1 22. Rxc1
g5 23. Bxd7 Kxd7 24. Be5 $18 {[%csl Ge5,Rh7] 1-0 Gyimesi,Z (2610)-Bindrich,F 
(2512)/Germany 2008/CBM 124 (29)  What a hopeless position for black's bishop..
.}) 15. h4 h6 (15... h5 {[%csl Rg6,Rh5] is another, but strategically more
risky, way to stop h4-h5.} 16. Ne2 $1 {[%cal Ge2f4] A familiar manoeuvre} Bd6
17. Be3 Ne5 18. Nf4 Rc8 (18... Nxc4 $6 {would seem to alleviate black's
problems somewhat, but in fact after} 19. Rxc4 b5 20. Rc2 Bxf4 21. Bxf4 bxa4
22. Kf2 f6 23. Bd6 $16 {[%csl Rg6,Rg8][%cal Gh1a1,Ga1a4,Gc2c7] white has a
strong initiative. For example,} Kd7 24. Rd1 Rgc8 25. Bb8+ $1 $18) 19. Bb3
Rxc1+ 20. Bxc1 Ke7 21. Ke2 Rc8 {This position arose in 1/2-1/2 Topalov,V (2805)
-Anand,V (2787)/Sofia 2010/CBM 136 (44). Black has managed to develop his
kingside rook, but he still has not solved the issue of Bg6.} {Here I suggest
a small improvement over the original game:} 22. g3 $146 {[%cal Gg3f4,Gg3h4]
supporting both the knight and the pawn in some variations.} Rc6 23. Be3 $14 {
Since black did not solve the issue of his bishop, white enjoys a small plus.
The following variations confirm this assessment:} Nc4 (23... Bc5 24. Nxg6+
Nxg6 25. Rc1 $14) (23... f6 24. Nxg6+ Nxg6 25. f4 Nf8 26. Rg1 $14 {[%cal Gg3g4]
}) 24. Bd4 Be5 25. Rd1 Bxd4 26. Rxd4 Ne5 27. Rb4 $14) 16. Kf2 Bd6 17. h5 Bh7 {
In this position, strong Russian GM Jakovenko found a great way to re-arrange
his pieces:} 18. Nd1 $1 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gd1e3,Ge3c4]} Rc8 19. Ne3 Ke7 20. Be2
{[%cal Ge3c4]} Be5 21. Bxe5 Nxe5 22. b4 $1 f6 23. a5 $14 {[%csl Rb7] Fixing
black's pawns on the queenside.} Rgd8 24. Rxc8 Rxc8 25. Rb1 {[%csl Rh7][%cal
Gb4b5] White is planning to target the b7 pawn and black bishop is nowhere to
help them.} Nc6 26. Nc4 {[%csl Gc4] The knight finally assumes its ideal
position.} f5 $5 {[%cal Gh7e4]} 27. Bd3 fxe4 28. fxe4 Bg8 29. b5 axb5 30. Rxb5
Rc7 31. e5 $1 $16 {[%csl Rg8] 1-0 Jakovenko,D (2737)-Ma,Z (2463)/Doha QAT 2015/
The Week in Chess 1102 (49)  The final position shows the dominance of white's
strategy in locking down the light-squared bishop.}) 14. Bb5 {By no means
forced, but the most principled.} a6 15. Bxd7+ Kxd7 16. Ke2 {[%csl Rd7][%cal
Gh1d1,Ga1c1] By taking on d7, white exposed black king on the d-file, which
will buy him some time to activate his rooks.} f6 {[%cal Gg6f7,Yf7e8,Ye8c6,
Ge6e5] Black uses the first opportunity to try and activate his bishop.} 17.
Rhd1 Ke8 ({The run towards queenside starting with} 17... Kc7 {[%cal Gc7b8]
looks reasonable, but white can prevent it with forceful play:} 18. e5 $1 Be7
19. Ba7 $1 {[%csl Rc7] A nice touch.} Be8 $8 {Black can finally use this
bishop, but only for defense.} (19... b6 20. Rac1 Kb7 21. Rd7+ Rc7 22. Rxc7+
Kxc7 23. Nd5+ $18) 20. Rac1 Bc6 21. a5 {[%csl Gb6]} fxe5 22. Ne4 $36 {and
black is almost paralyzed.}) (17... Bd6 $2 {[%cal Gd7e7] looks too good to be
true. Simply:} 18. e5 fxe5 19. Bxe5 Rc6 20. Bxg7 Rg8 21. Be5 $18) 18. Rac1 {
This poses some problems for black on the c-file.} (18. Rd2 $6 {is too slow.}
Bb4 19. Rad1 Ke7 20. Bb6 Be8 $11 {[%cal Ge8c6]}) 18... Be7 ({If} 18... Rc6 {
then white can seize the initative with:} 19. Na2 $1 Rxc1 20. Nxc1 Be7 21. Bb6
$1 {[%csl Gb6,Rh8]} e5 22. Nd3 $14 Bf7 $2 {Black succumbed to the pressure.} (
22... Kf7 {[%cal Gf7e6] was necessary, although the endgame after} 23. Rc1 Bd6
24. Bc7 Ke6 25. Bxd6 Kxd6 26. Nc5 Rb8 27. b4 $14 {[%csl Ra6,Rb7,Gc5][%cal
Ga4a5] is far from pleasant for black.}) 23. Rc1 Bd8 24. a5 $16 Ke7 25. Rc8 Re8
26. Rb8 Bc4 27. Rxb7+ Kf8 28. Ke3 $18 {1-0 Maletin,P (2545)-Amonatov,F (2650)/
Novokuznetsk 2008 (49)}) 19. Bb6 {[%cal Gd1d7] The most precise move, exposing
d7 square.} (19. a5 {was tried by Wesley So, but is inaccurate due to} Kf8 $1 {
[%cal Gg6e8]} 20. Na2 Kf7 21. Bb6 Rxc1 22. Rxc1 Bd6 23. Bc7 Ke7 24. Ke3 Kd7 25.
Bxd6 Kxd6 26. Nc3 Be8 27. Rd1+ Ke7 $11 {1/2-1/2 So,W (2674)-Nielsen,P (2700)/
Amsterdam 2010/CBM 138 (48)}) 19... Rf8 {[%cal Gf8f7,Gf7d7]} (19... Rc6 $6 20.
a5 Rf8 (20... Bd6 $2 21. Nb5) 21. Na4 $16 {[%csl Rc6]}) 20. a5 {Again,
precision is required.} (20. Na2 $6 {is premature due to} Rxc1 21. Nxc1 e5 $1
22. Nd3 f5 $1 $11 {1/2-1/2 Atalik,S (2607)-Mastrovasilis,D (2588)/Kalamaria
2010/CBM 138 Extra/[Atalik,S] (31)}) 20... Rf7 {The most stubborn move.} ({
Anand's choice was more risky:} 20... f5 {trying to free the bishop at once}
21. e5 {[%csl Ge5]} Bg5 (21... f4 $2 22. Ne4 Rxc1 23. Rxc1 Bxe4 24. fxe4 $16 {
with inevitable invasion of the 7th rank.}) 22. Be3 $14 (22. Ra1 $2 Bf4 $132)
22... f4 $6 {Here Anand missed Topalov's strong intermezzo.} (22... Bxe3 {was
safer, though black still struggles to equalize after} 23. Kxe3 f4+ 24. Kd4 Ke7
25. Ne4 Bxe4 26. Kxe4 $14) 23. Ne4 $1 {[%cal Ge4d6] Topalov rarely misses such
tactical opportunities.} Rxc1 24. Nd6+ Kd7 25. Bxc1 $16 {[%csl Gd6] and he
went on to win this superior endgame: 1-0 Topalov,V (2805)-Anand,V (2787)/
Sofia 2010/CBM 136/[Rogozenco,D] (54)}) 21. g3 $14 {White should be patient
too.} ({Since} 21. Na4 Rxc1 22. Rxc1 {allows} Bd6 $11) 21... Rc4 (21... Bf8 {
[%cal Gf7d7] seems logical, but fails to another one of small tactics white
has in this position:} 22. Na2 Rxc1 23. Rd8+ $1 Ke7 24. Nxc1 $16) 22. Na4 $1
Rxc1 23. Rxc1 Bd6 24. Ke3 e5 25. h4 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Re8,Rf7,Rg6] with a
pleasant advantage as black's pieces are still tangled up on the kingside.
Defending such positions with black for a long time is no fun, take my word
for it - I used to play the Slav myself!} *

