[White "Classical Slav"]
[Black "CHAPTER 4: 6...e6 7.f3 Bb4"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D17"]
[Annotator "GM Kuljasevic, Davorin"]
[PlyCount "53"]
[EventDate "2006.03.11"]
[SourceDate "2016.01.25"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 Bf5 6. Ne5 e6 7. f3 Bb4 {[%cal
Gb4e1] This variation, invented by late Andre Cheron - a famous endgame
composer, leads to some very interesting chess. Black is ready to sacrifice a
piece after the most principled move 8.e4. An enormous body of theory has
accumulated over the years in the line starting with 8.e4 Bxe4 9.fxe4 Nxe4 and
studying it properly takes a lot of time, which may not be the most practical
solution. I remember once Alexander Khalifman said it took him two weeks to
analyze a particular branch of this variation to find equality for black.
Secondly, I am not convinced that white can even count on any tangible
advantage if black plays the best moves. Even if he does, positions that arise
are quite unusual and seem to be easier to play for black as he has a clear
plan and white is not well co-ordinated. Therefore, I have decided to
recommend a bit less theoretical, though perfectly playable:} 8. Nxc4 (8. e4
Bxe4 9. fxe4 Nxe4 10. Bd2 ({The first ever game in this line ended
ungloriously for the white player after:} 10. Qf3 Qxd4 $1 11. Qxf7+ Kd8 12.
Qxg7 $4 Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 Qf2+ 14. Kd1 Nxc3# {0-1 Przepiorka,D-Cheron,A/The Hague
1928/EXT 2002/[ChessBase]}) 10... Qxd4 11. Nxe4 Qxe4+ 12. Qe2 Bxd2+ 13. Kxd2
Qd5+ 14. Kc2 Na6 15. Nxc4 O-O 16. Qe5 Rab8 17. a5 f6 18. Qxd5 cxd5 {leads to
an endgame where white retains chances for a small edge, though black is
super-solid and may even play for a win with his passed pawns if white does
something wrong.}) 8... O-O ({As in variation from CHAPTER 3, black can also
try to immediately attack white center with} 8... c5 9. dxc5 Qxd1+ (9... Bxc5 {
is inaccurate and hands white the initiative after} 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. e4 Bg6
12. Bg5 $36 {[%cal Ge4e5]} Kc8 13. Nb5 {[%csl Gd6]} Nc6 14. Rc1 Nd7 15. Bf4 $14
{1/2 (21) Gupta,A (2652)-Vallejo Pons,F (2705) Moscow RUS 2012 (21)}) 10. Kxd1
O-O (10... Bxc5 $6 {is similar to 9...Bxc5} 11. e4 Bg6 12. Nb5 {[%csl Rc7,Rd6]}
Kd7 13. Ne5+ Kd8 14. Bf4 Nbd7 15. Nd3 a6 16. Nd6 Bxd6 17. Bxd6 Ne8 18. Ba3 $16
{1-0 Levin,N-Bagirov,V/Kharkov 1967/URS-ch (38)}) 11. e4 Bg6 {and now the bold}
12. Nd6 $1 $14 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gd6b7] promises white material advantage. In
the following game black tried to play for compensation with} b6 13. cxb6 axb6
14. Ndb5 Na6 15. Be3 Nd7 16. Ke1 Nac5 17. Kf2 $14 {but white held his own and
eventually won in 1-0 Cernousek,L (2440)-Straka,V (2259)/Kouty nad Desnou 2012/
CBM 148 Extra (73)}) ({In case of the tempting} 8... Nd5 9. Bd2 $1 {[%cal
Ge2e4]} Qh4+ $6 10. g3 Qxd4 {white is winning by force:} 11. e4 $1 Nxc3 12.
bxc3 Bxc3 13. Ra2 Bxe4 14. Qc1 $3 $18 {A powerful quiet move.} Bxf3 (14... Bd3
15. Qxc3 Qxc3 16. Bxc3 Bxf1 17. Rxf1 O-O 18. Ke2 $18 {1-0 Giri,A (2588)
-Harikrishna,P (2672)/Wijk aan Zee NED 2010/The Week in Chess 793 (55)}) 15.
Bxc3 Qe4+ 16. Kf2 $18 {[%csl Re4,Rf3][%cal Gc4d6,Gc4d2]}) 9. Kf2 $5 {[%csl Gf2]
A very interesting move, which is completely new by historical standards - it
was first played in 2009 by French GM Fressinet. It is hard to imagine that
such an unorthodox idea could even come into consideration of the 20th century
theoreticians. Yet, as the current theory stands, black has still not shown
how to equalize comfortably against 9.Kf2!} ({The main reason for playing 9.
Kf2 can be understood when we see what happens if white plays e2-e4 with his
king on e1:} 9. e4 $2 Nxe4 $1 10. fxe4 Qh4+ 11. Kd2 Qxe4 $36 {[%csl Rd2] and
white king is in big trouble.}) 9... c5 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Gc5d4] Principled.} ({
Slower moves allow e2-e4 and do not equalize: 1)} 9... Nbd7 10. e4 Bg6 11. Be2
Qe8 {[%cal Ge6e5]} (11... c5 12. Na2 Ba5 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. Be3 $14) 12. Qb3 a5
13. Na2 Be7 14. Be3 c5 15. Rhd1 cxd4 16. Bxd4 $14 {1/2-1/2 Wagner,D (2569)
-Lampert,J (2448)/Biel 2015/CBM 167 Extra (26)}) ({2)} 9... Bg6 10. e4 Qc7 {
[%cal Gc6c5]} 11. Qb3 c5 12. Na2 $1 {[%csl Rb4] A standard reaction against c5
when black bishop is on b4.} Nc6 13. Nxb4 cxb4 14. Be3 Rfd8 15. Rd1 Rd7 16. Be2
(16. Ne5 $5 {is an interesting pawn sacrifice played by Ding and Giri, but
white can achieve a pleasant advantage with less risk. 1-0 (41) Ding Liren 
(2679)-Paragua,M (2521) Ho Chi Minh City VIE 2012}) 16... Rad8 17. g3 Nxd4 18.
Bxd4 Rxd4 19. Qxb4 Rxd1 20. Rxd1 Rxd1 21. Bxd1 $14 {[%csl Rg6] As in the line
from CHAPTER 3, black stands worse  because of misplaced bishop on g6.}) 10. e4
{Using the fact that cxd4 loses a piece to 11.Na2.} Bxc3 (10... Bg6 {is the
alternative, leading to interesting play as well:} 11. Na2 Nc6 (11... Ba5 12.
Be3 cxd4 13. Qxd4 Qxd4 14. Bxd4 Nc6 15. Bc5 Rfd8 16. Nxa5 Nxa5 17. Be3 $14 {
[%csl Ge3,Gf1,Rg6] is quite pleasant for white.}) 12. Nxb4 Nxb4 (12... cxb4 $2
13. Be3 $16) 13. Qb3 $1 {A very important move, played first by young Swedish
GM Grandelius. Now black needs to sacrifice something on e4 if he doesn't want
to end up ih a strategically inferior position. Let us see the possible lines:}
Nxe4+ (13... Qxd4+ 14. Be3 Nxe4+ 15. Kg1 $1 {[%csl Gg1] King is completely
safe here.} Qd5 16. Rd1 Qh5 17. fxe4 Bxe4 18. Rd2 Rad8 19. h4 $1 $14 {[%cal
Gh1h3,Gf1e2]}) (13... Bxe4 $5 14. fxe4 Qxd4+ (14... Nxe4+ 15. Kg1 Qxd4+ 16. Be3
Qd5 17. Be2 $14) 15. Be3 Qxe4 16. Be2 Qf5+ 17. Kg1 b6 18. Rf1 Qg6 19. h4 $14 {
[%cal Gh4h5,Gh1h3] 1-0 Sarkar,J (2437)-Gonzalez,B (2461)/Cochabamba BOL 2013/
The Week in Chess 967 (29)}) 14. fxe4 Bxe4 (14... Qxd4+ 15. Be3 Qxe4 16. Be2
Rad8 (16... Qh4+ 17. Kg1 Rfd8 18. Bf2 Qe7 19. Qc3 b6 20. h4 Be4 21. Rh3 $14 {
[%csl Gc3,Gc4,Rc5,Ge2,Re6,Gf2,Rf7,Gh3] 1/2-1/2 Mareco,S (2580)-Felgaer,R (2585)
/Montevideo URU 2013/The Week in Chess 964 (65) was another important game for
this line. As we can see in all these variations black has three pawns for the
piece, which promises him compensation. However, two things favor white
compared to similar positions in 8.e4 line. Firstly, many pieces are still on
the board which makes it easier for white to use his extra piece and secondly,
black's extra pawns are not connected and mobile. In that sense, I believe
that once white untangles with Kg1, Be3, h4, Rh3, he should be in the driver's
seat.}) 17. Rhc1 Nd3+ 18. Bxd3 Rxd3 19. Rc3 $14) {Here white could have
probably done better by playing} 15. dxc5 $1 $146 {as suggested by GM Ftacnik}
({although} 15. Bd2 {was good too in 1-0 Grandelius,N (2556)-Hector,J (2560)/
Malmo 2012/CBM 149 (51)}) 15... Nc2 16. Ra2 {The following lines prove white's
advantage:} Qd5 (16... Qf6+ 17. Kg1 Rfd8 18. Qc3 Rd1 19. Qxf6 gxf6 20. Bh6 Bd3
21. Nd2 Bxf1 22. Nxf1 Rc8 23. h4 $16) (16... Qd1 17. Bf4 Qe1+ 18. Kg1 $16) 17.
Qc3 Qxc5+ 18. Ne3 Qg5 19. Nxc2 Qf5+ 20. Kg1 Rac8 21. Bc4 Bxc2 22. b3 Bxb3 23.
Qxb3 Qe4 24. Kf2 Rxc4 25. Re1 $14) 11. bxc3 Bxe4 12. fxe4 Nxe4+ 13. Kg1 {[%csl
Gg1]} Nxc3 14. Qe1 cxd4 {Black wins four pawns for the piece in this instance,
but white gets a breather.} 15. Ba3 Re8 ({Sacrificing the rook for a bunch of
pawns} 15... Nc6 16. Bxf8 Qxf8 {is a cool idea, but after all, a rook is a
rook!} 17. h4 $14 {The position is complicated, but with accurate play white
should have the upper hand, as we can see in the following games:} Qc5 18. Nd2
Nb4 (18... Ne5 19. Rh3 Ng4 20. Bd3 Ne3 {1-0 Mchedlishvili,M (2625)-Bakre,T 
(2454)/Al Ain 2014/CBM 164 Extra (43)} 21. Ne4 $16) 19. Qf2 Rd8 20. Rh3 $14 {
1-0 Ding,L (2547)-Zhou Jianchao (2652)/Danzhou 2010 (38)}) 16. Nd6 Re7 17. Nb5
Rd7 18. Nxc3 dxc3 19. Qxc3 Nc6 20. h4 {[%cal Gh1h3] A known motive to activate
the idle rook.} Rc8 $1 (20... Nd4 {was another try, but white slowly took over:
} 21. Rc1 Qf6 22. Rh3 Rad8 23. Bb2 e5 24. Kh1 Qf2 25. Ba1 Nc6 26. Qe3 $16 {1-0
Jakovljevic,V (2377)-Bykov,A (2278)/Vienna 2011/CBM 143 Extra (51)}) 21. Rc1
Ne7 22. Qb3 Rxc1 23. Bxc1 Nf5 24. Bg5 Qa5 25. Rh3 h6 26. Be3 Nxe3 27. Rxe3 $14
{After making the best moves, black will still be struggling for a draw,
though his chances have increased after trading some pieces. Do not let the
final result of this game fool you - white blundered a piece in the endgame
where he was still trying to win.  0-1 Zhou,J (2636)-Batchuluun,T (2427)/
Shenzhen 2011/CBM 143 Extra (39)} *

