1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 Bf5 6. Ne5 Na6 {[%csl Gc2][%cal
Ga6b4] Among the alternatives to Nbd7 and e6, this is the most prominent one.
Black aims to bring his knight to b4 and in some lines tease white with Nc2/
Bc2 ideas.} (6... c5 $6 {should be answered vigorously as in the following
game:} 7. e4 $1 Nxe4 8. Qf3 e6 9. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 10. g4 Nxc3 11. gxf5 Qd5 12.
fxe6+ Ke8 (12... Kxe6 13. Qg4+ Kf7 14. Bg2 Qe6+ 15. Qxe6+ Kxe6 16. bxc3 $16)
13. Qf7+ Kd8 14. bxc3 Be7 15. Rg1 Rf8 16. Bg2 $18 {1-0 Lehmann,Z (2275)-Varga,
P (2395)/Budapest 1997/CBM 059 Extra (34)}) ({just as well as} 6... Nd5 7. e4
$1 Nxc3 8. Bxc4 $3 {[%cal Gc4f7] How often do you see such flashy moves in the
Slav?} e6 9. bxc3 Bxe4 10. Qh5 g6 11. Qe2 Bd5 12. O-O Bxc4 13. Qf3 $1 {
Intermediate move, provoking a weakness.} f6 14. Nxc4 Be7 15. Re1 $36 {[%csl
Ra8,Rb8,Gc4,Re8,Gf3,Rh8][%cal Gb1b7,Ge1e6,Gc1h6] with a tremendous initiative.}
) (6... Qc7 {can just lead to our main line by transposition:} 7. Nxc4 Nbd7 8.
g3 {- CHAPTER 8-10}) {Here we should play in a more restrained manner,} 7. e3 (
{as our usual} 7. f3 {is not as effective due to:} Nd7 8. Nxc4 e5 $1 9. e4 exd4
10. Qxd4 Nb4 $15 {with serious counterplay for black.}) 7... Nb4 8. Bxc4 e6 ({
Of course not} 8... Nc2+ $4 9. Qxc2 Bxc2 10. Bxf7#) 9. O-O {[%csl Ge5]
Compared to the line 6.e3 of the Classical Slav, white's knight on e5 can not
be challenged by the knight from b8. Here, black can try to do the same with
his bishop instead:} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5]} ({An interesting alternative,
played by Kramnik is} 9... Bc2 $5 10. Qe2 Nd7 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd7e5]
attacking Ne5 with the other knight, but also wasting valuable time in the
opening.} 11. Nxd7 Qxd7 {Here, white should use his development advantage and
play without hesitation} 12. e4 $1 ({Carlsen played more restrained} 12. a5 Be7
13. Na2 Nxa2 14. Rxa2 Bg6 15. Rd1 O-O 16. e4 Rad8 17. f3 Kh8 18. Bf4 f5 $132 {
but ultimately failed to get anything tangible in 1/2-1/2 Carlsen,M (2775)
-Kramnik,V (2788)/Moscow 2008/CBM 126 Extra (34)}) 12... Qxd4 13. Be3 Qd7 14.
Rac1 Bd3 15. Bxd3 Qxd3 16. Qf3 $32 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gf1d1] White's initiative
is quite serious, as Carlsen's second demonstrated in the following game:} Qd8
17. Qg3 {[%csl Rg7]} Qa5 18. Rfd1 h5 19. h4 Rg8 20. Bg5 $1 {[%csl Re8]} Na6 21.
Rd2 Qc7 22. Bf4 Qa5 23. Rcd1 $18 {1-0 Hammer,J (2610)-Hector,J (2609)/Malmo
SWE 2010/The Week in Chess 812 (41)}) (9... Be7 {does not seem to be as
consistent as Bd6.} 10. Qe2 {[%cal Ge3e4]} Bc2 {Kramnik's move in this version
is also interesting, in order to avoid e3-e4.} (10... h6 {is passive and gives
white a thematic advantage after:} 11. e4 Bh7 12. Rd1 O-O 13. Bf4 $16 {[%csl
Yc3,Yc4,Gd4,Ge4,Ye5,Yf4] Albeit solid, black's position is very passive and
since white controls the center with pawns and pieces, it does not look like
he will be able to make any of typical pawn breaks work any time soon. The
following game demonstrates white's dominance:} Qa5 14. Bb3 $1 {[%cal Ge5c4]}
Rad8 15. Nc4 Qh5 16. f3 Nd7 17. Bc7 Ra8 18. a5 Kh8 19. Bd6 Rae8 20. Bxe7 Rxe7
21. Nd6 $16 {1-0 Smejkal,J (2565)-Torre,E (2505)/Thessaloniki 1984/EXT 1997 
(52)}) {Among many possibilities, I believe the most promising one is} 11. Bd2
$1 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gf1c1,Gc3a2] aiming at Bc2 with Rfc1 and Na2 as quickly as
possible.} Nd7 (11... O-O 12. Rfc1 h6 13. Na2 $1 Nxa2 14. Rxc2 Nb4 15. Rcc1 $14
{[%csl Gc4,Gd2,Ge5] White's advantage is small, but stable.} Rc8 (15... a5 $142
16. Bc3 $14 {[%cal Ge3e4]}) 16. a5 $1 $16 {1-0 Dautov,R (2555)-Shabalov,A 
(2465)/Tashkent 1987/EXT 2002 (36)}) 12. Nxd7 Qxd7 {and here we can react
exactly the same way as in the game Hammer - Hector:} 13. e4 $1 Qxd4 14. Be3
Qd8 15. Rac1 Bd3 16. Bxd3 Qxd3 17. Qg4 {The only difference between two
positions is that black bishop is on e7 instead of f8. This is, of course, a
better version for black, but still suspicious.} O-O (17... g6 18. Rcd1 Qa6 19.
Bh6 $40 {[%csl Re8]}) 18. Rfd1 f5 {1-0 Shulman,Y (2616)-Nogueiras Santiago,J 
(2574)/Dresden 2008/CBM 128 (48)} (18... Qa6 19. Rd7 $40 {[%csl Gd7]}) 19. Qh5
Qa6 20. Rd7 Rf7 21. Rcd1 $40 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Gd7f7]}) 10. Qe2 h6 {Saving the
bishop.} ({Black can play more extravagantly:} 10... Nc2 $5 11. Rb1 Nd5 (11...
Bxe5 $6 12. dxe5 Ng4 {has been basically refuted by Hungarian GM Gymesi:} 13.
e4 $1 Nd4 14. Qd3 $1 Nxe5 15. Qg3 {[%cal Gg3g7]} Nxc4 (15... f6 16. Qxg7 Rf8
17. exf5 Nxc4 18. Qxb7 Nd6 19. Qxh7 $18 {1-0 Gyimesi,Z (2602)-Cramling,P (2515)
/Gibraltar 2006/CBM 110 Extra (44)}) 16. Qxg7 Rf8 17. b3 $1 {and black
position collapses} Qd6 18. bxc4 O-O-O 19. exf5 Nf3+ 20. gxf3 Rg8 21. Qg3 Rxg3+
22. hxg3 $18) {Here white has a few calmer options, but he can also play for
the advantage aggresively with} 12. Bxd5 exd5 13. g4 Bg6 14. f4 $1 {[%csl Rc2,
Rg6]} (14. Nxg6 $2 hxg6 15. Qxc2 Rxh2 $40) 14... Nb4 15. f5 f6 $8 16. fxg6 fxe5
17. e4 $1 {The key move that opens up the center and the bishop on c1. The
position is crazy, but white should have better chances, for example:} hxg6 18.
exd5 Qb6 {1-0 Iordachescu,V (2592)-Krivoshey,S (2553)/Calvi 2006/CBM 110 Extra
(41)} {and now very strong was} 19. Bg5 $1 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gg5d8]} Qxd4+ 20.
Kh1 {and black king is in dire straits. Black has problems even if he forces
queen trade} Qd3 21. Qxd3 Nxd3 22. dxc6 $16 {[%csl Rd3,Rd6][%cal Gb1d1]}) 11.
e4 Bh7 12. Bf4 O-O 13. Rad1 Qe7 ({Alternatively,} 13... Qc7 14. Bg3 a6 {1-0
Wojtaszek,R (2737)-Pakleza,Z (2498)/Katowice 2015/CBM 165 Extra (131)} 15. f4
$36 {looks very good for white, as the thematic} c5 {fails due to} 16. Nxf7 $1
Rxf7 17. e5 $16) 14. Bg3 $1 {[%cal Gg3h4,Gf2f4] White threatens to launch a
kingside offensive with Bh4, f4-f5 etc. Black has several options at his
disposal, none of them fully satisfactory:} c5 {Looking for counterplay in the
center immediately is relatively the best.} (14... Bc7 {[%cal Gc7b6]} 15. Bh4
g5 16. Bg3 Rad8 17. f4 Bb6 {1-0 Stefansson,H (2580)-Nabaty,T (2597)/Teplice
2015/CBM 167 Extra (39)} {and here white should have just ignored the d-pawn
and continued to apply the pressure with} 18. fxg5 Rxd4 19. Rxd4 Bxd4+ 20. Kh1
Bxe5 21. Bxe5 Nd7 22. Bg3 hxg5 23. Rd1 e5 24. Qg4 $40) (14... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]
is not critical} 15. Bh4 g5 16. Bg3 b5 17. axb5 axb5 18. Bb3 $16 Nd7 19. Nxd7
Qxd7 20. f4 Be7 21. fxg5 hxg5 22. Be5 f6 23. Qg4 $1 $18 {1-0 Shankland,S (2656)
-Hector,J (2485)/Helsingor 2015/CBM 167 Extra (30)}) 15. dxc5 Bxc5 16. Kh1 Rad8
17. f4 $36 {[%csl Gc4,Ge4,Ge5,Gf4,Gg3,Rh7] White was doing great in 1-0 Eames,
R (2263)-Purdon,C (2099)/England 2013/EXT 2014 (37)} *

