[Black "CHAPTER 6: 7...Nb6"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D17"]
[Annotator "GM Kuljasevic, Davorin"]
[PlyCount "37"]
[EventDate "2006.03.11"]
[SourceDate "2016.01.25"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 Bf5 6. Ne5 Nbd7 7. Nxc4 Nb6 {As
I mentioned in the introduction, this flexible variation (especially connected
with the subsequent a7-a5) was not at all popular until early 2000's when Ivan
Sokolov found some interesting ideas for black. Over the years, it has become
a reliable alternative to 7...Qc7, at times even surpassing it in popularity.}
8. Ne5 a5 {[%csl Gb6] This move proved to be necessary, as allowing white to
play a5 himself is not pleasant for black, to say the least.} ({For example:} 
8... e6 9. a5 Nbd7 10. a6 {[%csl Rb7,Rc6]} Nxe5 11. axb7 $1 {leads to a better
endgame for white, by force:} Rb8 12. dxe5 Qxd1+ 13. Nxd1 Ne4 14. Rxa7 $1 Bb4+
15. Nc3 Bc5 16. Nxe4 Bxa7 17. Nd6+ Kd7 {1-0 Veingold,A (2458)-Huebner,R (2608)/
Finland 2007/EXT 2009 (52)} {and now white can seal the deal with} 18. e4 Bg6
19. Ba6 $16 {[%csl Gb7,Rb8,Gd6,Rh8] Pawn on b7 and Nd6 are thorns in black's
side.} Bd4 20. Ke2 Bxe5 21. Nc4 $18) (8... Nbd7 {going for repetition is
punished by} 9. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Rb7,Rf7]} Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 ({or} 10... Ng4 11.
Qxb7 Nxe5 12. f4 Ng6 13. e4 Bd7 14. f5 $1 Ne5 15. Bf4 $18 {1-0 Kasparov,G 
(2805)-Timman,J (2635)/Riga 1995/CBM 047 (22)}) 11. e4 Be6 12. Qxb7 Nxe5 13. f4
Rb8 14. Qxa7 $16 {Black does not have sufficient compensation for the pawn.}
Nd7 15. f5 $1 Ra8 16. Qb7 Rb8 17. Qxc6 Rb6 {1-0 Kincs,I (2179)-Macsik,T (2283)/
Hungary 2011/EXT 2013 (48)} {and white could have crowned his previous play
with a strong queen sacrifice} 18. Qxb6 $1 Qxb6 19. fxe6 fxe6 20. Bb5 $18 {
[%csl Rd7,Re8,Rf8,Rh8]}) {I also mentioned in the introduction that many moves
have been tried at this junction: 9.f3, 9.g3, 9.e3 and 9.Bg5. White can
probably prove some plus in virtually all of them besides 9.Bg5, but there is
also a new kid on the block -} 9. h4 $5 {This move was launched by GM Anton
Korobov just 2 years ago and it has been a hit ever since. The overall score
is a whooping 75% for white, better than any other move. The sample size is
still small and this high percentage is probably bound to drop a bit in the
future, but it is definitely something to capture our attention and ride the
positive wave.   So what does white want to achieve with this aggresive move?
Well, in fact it is more prophylactic than anything as white kind of waits to
see which plan black will choose first and then reacts to it accordingly. I
would call it an improved version of all the moves that we mentioned,
especially of 9.f3. We will see why this is so as we examine black's answers:}
({Here are other lines followed by their critical moves:} 9. e3 Nbd7 (9... g6
$5)) (9. f3 Nfd7) (9. g3 e6) 9... Nbd7 {I find this to be the critical move,
just as I believe this move to be critical against 9.e3.} (9... e6 {This is
the critical move against 9.g3, but here white has} 10. f3 h6 (10... h5 $6 11.
e4 Bh7 12. Be3 Nfd7 13. Nd3 Be7 14. g3 O-O 15. Rc1 $16 {[%csl Rb6,Rh5,Rh7] is
just bad for black who is without any counterplay} Rc8 16. Ne2 Na8 17. Nef4 $18
{1-0 Khismatullin,D (2653)-Zoler,D (2527)/Jerusalem 2015/CBM 166/[Mokal,P] (27)
}) 11. e4 Bh7 12. Be3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge3,Ge4,Ge5,Rh7][%cal Gc6c5] We have seen
this type of position before - white will have an advantage unless black
manages to bring his light-squared bishop into the game or break up the center
with c6-c5. Let us see how things will turn out here:} Nfd7 (12... Be7 13. Qb3
{[%cal Gb3b6,Ge1c1]} Nfd7 14. O-O-O $1 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5] An enterprising
plan. White wants to hide his king on the queenside and use his h4 tempo to
continue the attack with g2-g4-g5 etc.} Qc7 15. Nd3 {Of course, the side with
more space does not change pieces.} O-O 16. Kb1 c5 {[%csl Gb5] Black is in
time to push c6-c5, but here another problem shows up - in this variation 
(after the inevitable 8...a5) pushing c6-c5 leaves b5 square undefended.} {
White, of course, uses this newly created weakness:} 17. Nb5 Qc6 18. dxc5 Nxc5
(18... Bxc5 19. Rc1 Bxe3 20. Rxc6 bxc6 21. Nd6 $16 {the queen sacrifice did
not help and white won in 1-0 Ding Liren (2781)-Bu Xiangzhi (2710)/Shenzhen
CHN 2015/The Week in Chess 1098 (35)}) 19. Bxc5 Bxc5 20. Ne5 $1 Bxe4+ {
Somewhat of a desparation, but black was already running out of moves.} 21.
fxe4 Qxe4+ 22. Nd3 Nd5 23. Re1 Qh7 24. Qc2 Be7 25. Ne5 $16 {1-0 Lei,T (2455)
-Shen,Y (2460)/Wuxi 2015/CBM 167 Extra (68)}) 13. Nd3 Bd6 {[%csl Rg3]} 14. Ne2
$1 {[%csl Gg3][%cal Ge2f4] covering the only weakness in white position, while
also bringing the knight toward the more interesting part of the board.} O-O (
14... Rc8 15. Rc1 O-O 16. Qb3 Kh8 17. Kf2 Be7 18. g3 f5 19. e5 $1 {[%csl Ge5,
Re6,Rh7] giving up the control over d5 square, but keeping the spatial
advantage and, more importantly, black bishop locked in on h7.} Nd5 20. Ndf4
Nxe3 21. Qxe3 Qb6 22. Nxe6 $16 {1-0 Ding Liren (2755)-Ma Qun (2609)/China CHN
2015/The Week in Chess 1101 (52)}) 15. Qb3 Qe7 16. Nef4 Rfe8 17. Kf2 $14 {
[%csl Rb6,Gd4,Rd7,Ge4,Gf2,Gf4,Rh7] This move looks familiar, doesn't it?} Bc7
18. Be2 Rab8 19. g4 $1 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gg4g5] White's position is so dominant
that he can even attack with his king on f2!} e5 $1 {For what it is worth,
this move has to be played or black would get steam-rolled.} 20. Nxe5 Nxe5 21.
dxe5 Qxe5 22. g5 $36 Bxe4 $1 {Another excellent practical decision by Armenian
Grandmaster bearing a famous first and last name.} 23. fxe4 Qxe4 24. g6 Bxf4
25. gxf7+ Kh8 26. fxe8=Q+ Rxe8 27. Bxf4 Qxf4+ 28. Bf3 Nd5 {[%csl Rf2] Black is
down a full rook, but has good practical compensation due to exposed white
king.  1/2-1/2 Swiercz,D (2617)-Petrosian,T (2623)/Abu Dhabi 2015/EXT 2016 (31)
} {White did not find the way to win the game, though the engine would be
merciless with} 29. Qd1 $16 {etc.}) (9... Nfd7 {This move is the best answer
against the most principled move 9.f3. However, here we have a huge difference
between these two lines.} 10. e4 Nxe5 11. exf5 Nec4 (11... Ned7 {In the 9.f3
line we reach a similar position with the only difference being white pawns on
f3 and h2. Here we have f2 and h4, which allows white to play:} 12. h5 $1 {
[%csl Re7,Gf5,Rf7,Rg7,Gh5,Rh7] stopping black from developing his kingside
naturally with g7-g6!} e6 13. fxe6 Qe7 14. Be2 Qxe6 15. O-O $16 {1-0 Abel,D 
(2441)-Petursson,M (2520)/Berlin GER 2015/The Week in Chess 1092 (38)}) 12. h5
$1 {works the same way as in case of 11...Ned7} e5 13. fxe6 Qe7 14. Bxc4 Nxc4
15. O-O $16 {1/2-1/2 Bluebaum,M (2600)-Michalik,P (2546)/Zillertal AUT 2015 
White has a significant advantage in both cases.}) ({Sometimes against 9.e3
black play} 9... g6 {Well, here white should definitely use his h-pawn:} 10. h5
$1 (10. f3 {was played in 1/2-1/2 Studen,D (2259)-Holt,C (2546)/Arlington 2015/
CBM 167 Extra (32), but it is not as convincing.}) 10... gxh5 11. e4 $1 {
Strong follow-up, reminiscent of some lines of Leningrad Dutch.} Nxe4 (11...
Bxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Nxf7 Kxf7 14. Qxh5+ Kg8 15. Qg4+ Bg7 16. Qxe4 Qxd4 17.
Qe6+ Kf8 18. Be2 $36) 12. Qxh5 Bg6 13. Nxg6 Nf6 14. Qe5 fxg6 15. Bd3 Kf7 (15...
Bg7 16. Rxh7 $1) 16. Ne4 $36) (9... h5 $6 {[%csl Rg5,Rh5] is a panicky move in
my opinion. There is no need for such drastic measures.} 10. f3 Nfd7 11. e4
Nxe5 12. exf5 Ned7 13. Qb3 Qc7 14. Be3 Nf6 15. Rc1 Rd8 16. Bf2 Nbd5 17. Bc4 e6
18. fxe6 fxe6 19. O-O $16 {1-0 Deac,B (2469)-Kopinits,A (2275)/Graz AUT 2016/
The Week in Chess 1110 (35)}) ({Finally,} 9... Nfd5 $6 {was played only once,
but it is good to see how it good punished:} 10. g4 $1 Be6 11. e4 Nb4 12. d5 $1
{[%cal Gf1b5,Gc6d5]} Bc8 13. Be3 {[%csl Rb6]} Nd7 14. Nc4 e5 15. d6 $18 {1-0
Swiercz,D (2617)-Petrov,N (2446)/Riga 2015/CBM 167 Extra (26)}) 10. Qb3 {[%csl
Gb7,Gf7][%cal Gb3f7,Gb3b7] The most principled move.} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd7 12. e4
Be6 13. Qxb7 Nxe5 {[%csl Gb7,Re1,Ge5,Re8][%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5] OK, the material
balance has been re-established. It is not simple to evaluate this position.
Obviously white has an easier development, but questions like: Is white queen
strong or misplaced? Is h4 useful or bad? Whose king is weaker? are still
waiting for an answer. Well, to answer these questions, we have to dig a bit
deeper.} ({There is not a big difference between the text and} 13... Rb8 14.
Qa7 ({apart from falling for the trick} 14. Qxc6 $2 Rb6) 14... Nxe5 (14... Ra8
{was perhaps an attempt to force a draw in 0-1 Shen,Y (2459)-Gunina,V (2528)/
China 2015/EXT 2016 (64)} {which can be best declined with} 15. Qe3 Nxe5 16.
Be2 $14) 15. Bf4 (15. Be2 $142 $14 {[%cal Ga7e3]}) 15... f6 16. Be2 Qb6 17.
Qxb6 Rxb6 18. Nd1 $1 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gf4d2,Gd2a5]} Rb4 19. Bd2 Rxe4 20. Bxa5
Nd3+ 21. Kf1 Nf4 {1/2-1/2 Li,S (2508)-Yu,R (2571)/China 2015/EXT 2016 (40)} 22.
Ba6 $14) 14. Be2 $5 $146 {This natural move is a suggested improvement over
the stem game, where 14.Bf4 has been played instead. When preparing for a game,
we need to always come up with these small improvements that were maybe not
analyzed by our opponent, in order to get him out of the comfort zone of his
home preparation.} (14. Bf4 Rb8 15. Qa6 Ra8 16. Qe2 Qb8 17. h5 {looked very
dangerous for black in 1-0 Korobov,A (2687)-Solak,D (2607)/Jerusalem 2015/CBM
166/[Mikhalchishin,A]} {but as GM Mikhalchishin pointed out, the unexpected
pawn sacrifice} g5 $1 18. Bxg5 Qb4 $44 {[%csl Gb4,Ge5,Ge6][%cal Gf8g7] would
give black good compensation for the pawn.}) 14... g6 {This is the most
logical continuation.} ({After the queen trade} 14... Qb8 15. Qxb8+ Rxb8 {
black runs into the problems with his a-pawn:} 16. Nd1 $1 $14 {[%csl Ra5,Gb2]
[%cal Gc1d2,Yd1b2,Gd2a5]}) (14... Rb8 {only helps white to evacuate his queen:}
15. Qa7 $14 {[%cal Ga7e3]}) 15. h5 Rb8 16. Qa7 Rg8 {Again, a difficult
position to evaluate. This is a perfect position for engines to do some work
while you are having lunch or taking a walk. Since my engine is not too strong,
I only came up with:} 17. f4 $5 {There are other possiblities as well.} Nd7 (
17... Ng4 18. Bf3 $14 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Ge4e5]}) (17... Nc4 18. hxg6 hxg6 19.
Bxc4 Bxc4 20. Be3 Rxb2 21. Rd1 $36) 18. Be3 $1 Rxb2 19. h6 $36 {[%csl Re8,Rf8,
Rg8] I prefer white in all lines, though admittedly the position is still
double-edged. Perhaps this will be the battleground of this variation in the
future.} *

