1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 Bf5 6. Ne5 Nbd7 7. Nxc4 {Before
we move on to the main line 7...Qc7, we have to mention two rare alternatives.
The first one} Nd5 {is actually not that bad, though it is not at all
challenging for white, in my opinion.} ({The second one is quite passive and I
cover it just so that we can get a better idea how to deal with passive setups
in the Classical Slav.} 7... e6 8. f3 Bb4 9. e4 Bg6 (9... Nxe4 $6 {idea does
not work now} 10. fxe4 Qh4+ 11. Kd2 Qxe4 {due to} 12. Nd6+ $1 $18) 10. Be2 O-O
11. O-O a5 (11... Qc7 {[%cal Gc6c5]} 12. Qb3 $1 {provoking a7-a5 which, as we
know from CHAPTER 6, weakens the b5 square in case black pushes his thematic
c6-c5.} a5 13. Kh1 e5 $6 (13... c5 14. Nb5 {[%csl Gb5]} Qb8 15. Be3 cxd4 16.
Bxd4 $16) 14. dxe5 Nc5 15. Qa2 Nfd7 16. Bf4 Ne6 17. Bg3 $18 {1-0 Maksimenko,A 
(2545)-Kavcic,U (2100)/Nova Gorica 1997/CBM 056 Extra (25)}) ({We already know
how to deal with} 11... c5 {simply} 12. Na2 $16 {[%csl Rb4]}) 12. Be3 Ne8 $5 {
[%cal Gf7f5]} 13. Bf2 f5 {At least black is doing something about the
light-squared bishop. Unfortunately, it does not quite work.} 14. exf5 exf5 15.
Na2 Be7 16. Qb3 Bf7 17. Qxb7 Bd5 18. Qb3 Nd6 19. Qc2 $16 {1-0 Mikhalevski,V 
(2525)-Bykhovsky,A (2455)/Rishon Le Ziyyon 1995/CBM 046 (27)}) 8. f3 {[%cal
Ge2e4] Business as usual.} e5 9. e4 Nxc3 10. bxc3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge4,Gf3]
White has the perfect center.} Be6 {Here I prefer to include} 11. Rb1 {[%cal
Gb1b7]} Qc7 12. Be3 Rd8 {Black omits playing f7-f6 for now.} (12... f6 13. Be2
Bf7 14. O-O Be7 15. f4 {Black has not castled and white already has the
initative.} O-O 16. fxe5 fxe5 {here white found a great resource:} 17. Qb3 $1 {
[%cal Gb3b7,Gb3g8] looks paradoxical to put the queen on the same diagonal as
bishop just to attack some pawn, but the idea is revealed on the next move.} b6
18. Rxf7 $1 Rxf7 19. Bg4 $16 {[%csl Re5,Rf7,Rg8][%cal Gg4d7,Gc4e5] with a
fantastic position for white in 1-0 Wells,P (2526)-Collins,S (2412)/Liverpool
2008/CBM 126 Extra (34)}) 13. Qc2 Be7 (13... b6 14. Bd3 Bxc4 15. Bxc4 Bd6 16.
g3 O-O 17. O-O Kh8 18. f4 f6 19. Qg2 $16 {1-0 Beliavsky,A (2659)-Karttunen,M 
(2466)/Panormo 2001/CBM 084 Extra}) 14. Be2 f6 {Here I would suggest an
improvement over the previous games:} 15. Bf2 $1 $146 {[%cal Gc4e3] This move
discourages b7-b5 push as the knight has a comfortable retreat on e3.} (15. O-O
O-O (15... b6 {this is very solid, but passive.} 16. Rbd1 Bf7 17. f4 $14 O-O {
Here Gelfand sacrificed an exchange} 18. dxe5 ({though he had an easier way} 
18. fxe5 fxe5 19. Bf2 Bd6 20. Bg3 $14 {[%csl Rd6,Re5]}) 18... fxe5 19. Rxd7 $5
Qxd7 20. Nxe5 $14 {[%csl Ge5] 0-1 Gelfand,B (2693)-Morozevich,A (2758)/
Mallorca 2004/CBM 104/[Huebner,R] (53)}) 16. Rfd1 b5 $1 {is a good idea to get
some breathing space, though white still keeps the advantage} {with} 17. axb5 (
17. d5 bxc4 $2 (17... cxd5 $142 18. exd5 bxc4 19. dxe6 Nb6 $11) 18. dxe6 Bc5
19. Kh1 $1 Bxe3 20. e7 $18 {1-0 Kuljasevic,D (2580)-Stojanovic,D (2487)/
Plovdiv 2012/CBM 148 (23)}) 17... cxb5 18. d5 Bxd5 19. Rxd5 bxc4 20. Qa2 $14)
15... O-O 16. O-O b6 (16... b5 $6 17. axb5 cxb5 18. Ne3 $16 {[%csl Rb5]}) 17.
Rfd1 Bf7 18. Ne3 $14 {[%csl Gc3,Rc7,Gd4,Rd7,Ye3,Ge4,Re7,Gf3,Rf7] Black is
solid, but very passive, while white has more than one way to improve his
position.} *

