1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 Bf5 6. Ne5 Nbd7 7. Nxc4 Qc7 {
[%cal Ge7e5] This is the main line and probably the most challenging one for
our direct approach. Black wants to break up white's pawn center immediately
with e7-e5. However, white can use the position of Qc7 to his advantage with:}
8. g3 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gc1f4]} e5 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Bf4 {[%cal Gf4c7] Quite an
unpleasant pin, forcing black to waste some time defending against it.} Nfd7
11. Bg2 f6 {[%cal Gf6e5] This solid move has been considered "a must" for a
long time, until Morozevich came up with 11...g5. Before we move on to 11...g5
and other moves, in this chapter we will examine the "old main line" - 11...f6.
} 12. O-O {Black has many possible ways to continue and we will examine the
most critical ones.} Nc5 {This active move, threatening Rd8 and Nb3 afterwards,
has been the most common in this position. However, new developments in this
line are beginning to discourage black from playing it.} ({The newest fashion
is "improved Morozevich":} 12... g5 $5 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gf6g5] and now 13.Ne3
does not work as 12.Ne3 does against 11...g5 since g5 pawn is defended here.
Therefore, the best is to play simply:} 13. Nxe5 gxf4 (13... Nxe5 14. Be3 $14 {
[%csl Ge6,Rf6,Rg5,Gh5] gives white a typical kind of advantage in this line,
more so considering black's weaknesses on the kingside.}) 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 (14...
O-O-O $6 {is a move that works in a similar position from 11...g5 line, but
not here:} 15. Qd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4a7,Gd4f4]} Bxd7 16. Qxa7 fxg3 17. hxg3 $16 {
1-0 Izzat,K (2480)-Li,Z (2311)/Melbourne AUS 2016/The Week in Chess 1105 (22)})
(14... Bxd7 {is also inaccurate due to} 15. e3 fxg3 16. Qh5+ $1 Ke7 17. fxg3
$40 {[%csl Re7][%cal Gf1f6] 1-0 Agopov,M (2440)-Issakainen,A (2197)/Finland
2014/EXT 2015 (28)}) 15. a5 $1 {[%csl Rb7,Rc6][%cal Ga5a6,Gg2b7] This motive
is very important in Qc7 line of Classical Slav. White is trying to create
some weaknesses on the queenside and black has to react.} fxg3 (15... Qxd1 16.
Raxd1 a6 {[%csl Gb6,Rb7,Gc5] This is necessary, otherwise white pushes a5-a6
and destroys black's queenside. However, now white has a clear structural
advantage as his 2 pawns are holding down 3 black pawns. All black pawns are
on light-squares, which is something that should make white bishop on g2 very
happy. In addition to that, white can sometimes use b6 and c5 squares to his
advantage. The only black compensation consists of the bishop pair and the
possibility to attack white pawns on a5 with Bb4.} 17. Ne4 $1 {[%cal Ge4f6,
Ge4d6]} ({Greedy} 17. gxf4 $6 {would allow black bishop pair to show its full
strength, as in the following game:} Be7 18. e4 Be6 19. Ne2 Bb3 20. Rd2 Bb4
$132 {[%csl Gb3,Gb4] 0-1 Colpe,M (2311)-Hector,J (2509)/Helsingor 2013/CBM 155
Extra (44)}) 17... Bxe4 18. Bxe4 $14 {[%csl Ra6,Rb7,Rc6,Rf6,Rh7] even with the
opposite colored bishops, white can play for the full point as black's shaky
pawn structure promises a plenty of targets for his rooks and bishop.} fxg3 (
18... Bb4 19. Rd3 $1 Bxa5 20. Ra1 Bc7 21. Rb3 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Ge4c6,Gb3b7,
Ga1a6]} Rb8 22. Rxb7 $1 Rxb7 23. Bxc6+ Ke7 24. Bxb7 $16) 19. fxg3 $5 {[%cal
Gf1f6]} Bc5+ (19... Bb4 20. Rxf6 Bxa5 21. Rd3 $36) 20. Kg2 Ke7 21. Rf5 $36) 16.
fxg3 $5 {The most dynamic continuation.} ({White can, of course, play more
classically with} 16. hxg3 Qxd1 17. Rfxd1 a6 18. Rd4 $1 $14 {[%csl Ra5,Rb4]
[%cal Gd4b4,Gd4h4] This is a very important move, controlling the 4th rank.
Wesley So continued to put pressure and eventually won the opposite colored
bishops endgame in 1-0 So,W (2775)-Akopian,V (2648)/Doha QAT 2015/The Week in
Chess 1103 (48)}) 16... a6 17. Be4 $1 {[%csl Ra8,Re8,Rf6,Rf8,Rh8] White needs
to play energetically in order to use black's lag in development.} Bh3 18.
Qxd7+ Bxd7 19. Rxf6 $14 {[%csl Gd7,Gf8] Black does not have any compensation
for the pawn, but white's technical task is not trivial due to black's bishop
pair.} Bg7 20. Rd6 O-O-O 21. Rad1 Kc7 22. Na4 h6 23. R1d3 Be5 24. Rg6 Bh3 25.
Kf2 Rdg8 26. Rf3 Rxg6 27. Rf7+ Kd6 28. Bxg6 $16 {1-0 Svane,R (2509)-Romanov,E 
(2613)/Stroebeck GER 2015/The Week in Chess 1068 (52)}) (12... Be6 {is a very
solid move that covers the weaknesses made by f6 move.} 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 (13...
fxe5 {is the old continuation and here white found a strong idea:} 14. Bg5 $1 {
provoking kingside weaknesses after h7-h6.} Bc5 (14... h6 15. Be3 {[%csl Gg6]}
Bc5 (15... Bb4 16. Qc2 {[%cal Gc3d5]} Nf6 17. a5 $1 {[%cal Ga1a4,Ga5a6] An
excellent multi-purpose move.} a6 18. Ra4 Bxc3 $6 (18... Bd6 19. Ne4 Nxe4 20.
Bxe4 $14) 19. Bb6 $1 Qf7 20. Qxc3 $16 {1-0 Dorfman,J (2585)-Miralles,G (2515)/
Meribel 1998/CBM 067/[Huebner,R] (42)}) 16. Qc2 $1 {[%cal Gc2g6]} O-O-O ({If} 
16... Bxe3 {white has a strong piece sacrifice:} 17. Nb5 $1 Qb6 18. Qg6+ Kd8
19. Nd6 {with a dangerous attack:} Ke7 20. a5 Bxf2+ 21. Rxf2 Qd4 22. e3 $1 Qg4
23. Qd3 $16) 17. Qg6 $1 $36 {with strong pressure for white, who used the g6
weakness in the optimal way in 1-0 Khalifman,A (2645)-Gabriel,C (2555)/Bad
Wiessee 1998/EXT 2000 (21)}) (14... Bb4 15. Qc2 $14 {[%cal Gc3d5]}) 15. Ne4 Bb4
16. Bd2 $1 {[%csl Gb4,Rg5][%cal Gd2b4,Ge4g5] Very nice maneouvers by Radjabov
over the last few moves.} Be7 17. Ng5 {winning the bishop pair.} Bxg5 18. Bxg5
a5 19. Qc2 O-O 20. Rad1 $14 {The bishop pair and better pawn structure are
sufficient for stable long-term advantage, but it is instructive to see how
Radjabov continued to put pressure on black's position by provoking small
weaknesses:} Nb6 21. Be3 Rfd8 22. Be4 $1 {[%csl Rg7,Rh7]} h6 23. Bf3 $36 {
[%csl Rg6][%cal Gc2g6] 1-0 Radjabov,T (2682)-Morozevich,A (2707)/Mainz 2005/
CBM 107 Extra (43)}) 14. a5 {The standard move, not only threatening a5-a6,
but also clearing a4 square for white pieces.} a6 15. Qa4 $1 {[%csl Ga5,Gb4]
[%cal Gc3d5] better than 15.Qc2 as it covers b4 square in addition to making
the Nd5 threat.} Bc5 (15... Bd6 16. Ne4 Be7 17. Rac1 O-O 18. Be3 Rae8 19. Bb6
Qb8 20. Nc5 $36 {[%csl Gb6,Rb7,Gc5] white can hardly do any better than this.
1-0 Obodchuk,A (2421)-Yamszhchikov,A (2096)/Ekaterinburg 2008/EXT 2009 (41)})
16. Rac1 (16. Nd5 Qf7 {is OK for black.}) 16... O-O 17. Ne4 Ba7 18. Nc5 $14 {
After this, there is no doubt as to who stands better, but let us go a bit
further to gain some deeper understanding about this kind of position:} Qf7 19.
Qb4 $1 {[%csl Rb7] An important decision by Grischuk. Instead of impulsively
taking the light-squared bishop with Nxe6, he forced the trade of dark-squared
bishop. He knew that dark-squared bishop is more valuable to black than
light-squared bishop in this type of position.} (19. Nxe6 Qxe6 $14 {[%csl Re6,
Rf5]}) 19... Bxc5 20. Qxc5 $14 {[%csl Rb6,Rd6]} Ng6 21. Be3 Rfd8 22. Rfd1 Bb3
23. Rd4 Rxd4 {1/2-1/2 Grischuk,A (2774)-Fedoseev,V (2659)/Berlin GER 2015/The
Week in Chess 1092 (97)} 24. Bxd4 $14 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gf2f4]}) (12... O-O-O {is
an exciting continuation where black is trying to fight for initiative
himself! However, it has been refuted with} 13. Rc1 $1 {[%cal Gc1c8,Yc3b5]} Nc5
14. Qe1 {[%cal Gb2b4]} a5 (14... Nb3 {would be too naive} 15. Nb5 $1 cxb5 16.
Nb6+ axb6 17. Rxc7+ Kxc7 18. Qc3+ Nc5 19. b4 $18) 15. Nb5 $1 {Nevertheless!}
cxb5 16. axb5 b6 17. b4 $1 {Clearing the a-file.} axb4 18. Qxb4 {[%csl Rb6,Gc4,
Rc8,Gf4,Gg2][%cal Gc1c8,Gf4c7] For the sacrificed piece, white has a strong
attack as black is completely tied down and his king does not feel safe. The
following variations demostrate problems that black is about to face:} Be6 (
18... Bd6 19. Bxe5 fxe5 20. Bc6 $1 {[%csl Gc6,Rc8]} Bd7 21. Rfd1 Bxc6 22. bxc6
{[%csl Rb6]} Qxc6 23. Nxb6+ Kc7 24. Nd5+ $18 {1-0 Mareco,S (2591)-Toniutti,E 
(2133)/Asuncion 2011/CBM 142 Extra (33)}) (18... g5 19. Bxe5 fxe5 {1/2-1/2
Sveshnikov,V (2411)-Tarasova,V (2292)/Albena 2013/CBM 154 Extra (32)} 20. Qc3
Bg7 (20... Be6 21. Ra1 Rd4 22. Ra8+ Kd7 23. Ra7 $1 Qxa7 24. Nxe5+ Ke8 25. Qxd4
$40) 21. Nxb6+ $1 Qxb6 22. Qf3 $18 {[%csl Rc8] Black king is bare naked and
the winter is coming...}) 19. Bxe5 ({Even stronger was immediately} 19. Ra1
$142 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Ga1a8]} Bxc4 20. Bxe5 Qxe5 21. Qxc4 Bd6 22. Qf7 $40)
19... fxe5 20. Ra1 $36 {[%csl Rc8]} Rd4 {In this critical moment in the game
0-1 Nielsen,P (2693)-Vallejo Pons,F (2705)/Beijing 2011/CBM 145 Extra (25)
white made a mistake and eventually event lost the game. He could have won had
he seen a strong quiet move Qa3 in the following line:} 21. Ra8+ Kd7 22. Bc6+
Ke7 23. Qa3 $1 {[%cal Ga8a7]} Bxc4 24. Ra7 Qxa7 25. Qxa7+ Kf6 26. f4 $18) (
12... Rd8 {is similar to 12...Be6, the only difference being that here it
forces white queen to go to an apparently less active square c1.} 13. Qc1 Be6
14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Ne4 {[%cal Ge4c5]} Bb4 {is the most solid attempt. White has
to play precisely to obtain the advantage:} (15... Qa5 {was played long time
ago by elite Soviet players:} 16. Bd2 Bb4 17. Bxb4 Qxb4 18. Qc5 (18. Qf4 Qe7
19. Qe3 a6 (19... b6 $1 $11 {[%csl Gc5]}) 20. Nc5 Bc8 21. b4 $14 {1-0
Levenfish,G-Flohr,S/Moscow 1936/HCL (45)}) 18... Qxc5 19. Nxc5 Bc8 20. b4 $14 {
[%csl Gb4,Rb7,Gc5,Rc6,Gg2] with a typical very pleasant endgame for white.}) (
15... Be7 16. Nc5 Bc8 17. Nd3 $5 {A cool idea.} O-O (17... Nxd3 18. exd3 Qd7
19. Rd1 O-O 20. Be3 $14 {[%cal Gd3d4,Gd4d5] black's pieces stand awkwardly and
white has a simple plan of rolling his d-pawn.}) 18. a5 a6 19. Nxe5 fxe5 20.
Be3 {[%csl Rb7,Re5] White enjoys a small advantage thanks to his superior pawn
structure.} Qd6 21. Bb6 Rde8 22. Qc2 Bf5 23. Be4 Bxe4 24. Qxe4 Bd8 25. Rad1 Qe6
26. Rd3 Bxb6 27. axb6 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Ge4,Re5] 1-0 Nguyen Ngoc Truong Son (2659)
-Le Tuan Minh (2393)/Ho Chi Minh City VIE 2015/The Week in Chess 1062 (47)})
16. Nc5 Bc8 {[%csl Gc8,Gd8] Courtesy of 12...Rd8.} 17. Bxe5 fxe5 {Here white
keeps the initiative with} 18. Qe3 $1 {[%csl Ra7,Rb4,Re5][%cal Gc5d3]} (18. Nd3
{was less impressive in} Bd6 19. b4 Bf5 20. Nc5 O-O 21. Qc4+ Kh8 22. Rac1 Qe7
$11 {1/2-1/2 Wojtaszek,R (2614)-Miton,K (2609)/Lublin 2008/CBM 123 (28)}) 18...
Bd2 19. Qb3 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gb3g8]} Qf7 20. Qc2 Ba5 21. Nd3 {[%csl Re5]} Bc7
22. Qc5 {[%cal Gc5e5,Gc5a7]} a5 23. Nxe5 Qe7 24. Qxe7+ Kxe7 $14 {winning a
pawn, though black is solid and active with his bishop pair, so winning the
game would take some more work. 1/2-1/2 Agrest,E (2561)-Krivoshey,S (2475)/
Cutro 2007/CBM 118 Extra (112)}) 13. Ne3 $1 {The importance of this move is in
tactical nuances which prevent black from playing Rd8.} Bg6 ({Immediate} 13...
Rd8 $6 {runs into tactical refutation} 14. Ncd5 $1 Qd7 (14... cxd5 15. Nxf5 $16
) 15. Nxf5 Qxf5 16. Nc7+ Ke7 17. Qe1 $1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ge1a5]} Kd7 18. Rd1+
Bd6 19. Qa5 Kc8 20. Rxd6 $1 Rxd6 21. Nd5 cxd5 22. Qxc5+ Rc6 23. Qxa7 $18 {
[%csl Ga7,Rc8,Gf4,Gg2] black saved himself by a miracle in 1/2-1/2 Gupta,A 
(2380)-Kuzubov,Y (2535)/Port Erin 2005/CBM 108 Extra (40)}) 14. b4 $1 Ne6 {The
knight has to retreat,} ({since} 14... Rd8 $6 {doesn't work again due to} 15.
Ned5 cxd5 16. bxc5 Bxc5 17. Nxd5 $16 {[%csl Gd5,Gf4,Gg2] with a dominant
position for white in 1/2-1/2 Wang,H (2696)-Sokolov,I (2669)/Sarajevo 2009/CBM
130 (46)}) 15. b5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gb5c6] Not only did white chase off the
knight from c5, but he was also in time to launch the minority attack against
black's queenside.} Rd8 16. Qb3 {We have reached the point where black has
many ways to continue the fight. While in none of them he reaches full
equality, the most promising one is} Nd4 (16... Bf7 {gives white an important
tempo to begin harvesting fruits of his minority attack:} 17. Bxe5 fxe5 18.
bxc6 bxc6 19. Rab1 {[%csl Ra7,Rc6][%cal Gb3b7]} Nc5 20. Qb2 Bg6 21. Rbd1 {
Black managed to fend off the raid on the 7th rank, but at the cost of delayed
kingside development.} Be7 22. Rxd8+ Bxd8 23. Nb5 $1 {[%csl Re8] This is an
excellent move, using temporary disharmony among black pieces and uncastled
king.} cxb5 24. Qxb5+ Nd7 25. Rd1 a6 26. Qc6 Bf7 27. Nf5 $18 {Black was
completely tied down in 1-0 Halkias,S (2548)-Drenchev,P (2412)/Kavala 2005/CBM
107 Extra (36)}) (16... Nxf4 {was played by a very strong player, but is even
more time-wasting than 16...Bf7.} 17. gxf4 Bf7 18. Qc2 Nd7 19. bxc6 bxc6 {so
far, every white move came with tempo in 1/2-1/2 Grischuk,A (2752)-Rublevsky,S
(2686)/Apatity 2011/CBM 145 Extra (31) and so should have the next move:} 20.
Nb5 $1 Qxf4 21. Qxc6 $18 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Gc6e8] and it is hard to believe
that black would get out of this alive.}) (16... Nc5 17. Qb2 Bd6 {as in 1-0
Kovacs,G (2393)-Macsik,T (2299)/Szombathely 2003/CBM 095 Extra (45) is a more
passive version of 16...Nd4 and 17...Bc5 idea.} {White can now seize the
initiative with} 18. a5 $36 {[%cal Ga5a6]} a6 19. bxc6 bxc6 20. Bxe5 $1 {
eliminates the defender of c6 pawn and c4 square.} Bxe5 21. Qb4 Bd6 22. Nc4 $16
{[%csl Gc4,Rc6]}) 17. Qb2 Bc5 {Black is one move away from fully completing
his development, in which case his position would be perfectly fine. White
have tried many approaches here and the one that clearly stands out is:} 18.
Ng4 $1 O-O (18... Ne6 {[%cal Gc5d4]} 19. Bxe5 fxe5 20. bxc6 bxc6 {looks quite
good for black at the first glance, that is until white plays} 21. Ne4 $1 Bd4
22. Qa2 {[%csl Re6]} Bf7 23. Qa3 $1 {[%cal Gg4f6] A beautiful idea. Black is
forced to trade queens} Qe7 (23... Bxa1 24. Nef6+ gxf6 25. Nxf6#) 24. Qxe7+
Kxe7 25. Rac1 h5 26. Ne3 Bxe3 27. fxe3 $16 {[%csl Rc6,Ge4,Re6,Rf7][%cal Gg2c6]
with great difficulties for black in the endgame 1-0 Ding,L (2654)-Ma,Q (2447)/
Hefei 2011/CBM 143 Extra (57)}) (18... Bh5 {is harmless} 19. h3 O-O 20. Ne4
cxb5 21. Bxe5 fxe5 22. Rac1 b6 23. e3 Ne6 24. axb5 $16 {[%csl Ra7,Gc6,Gd5,Ge4,
Re5] with complete domination on light-squares in 1-0 Shirov,A (2701)-Hector,J
(2588)/Malmo 2011/CBM 143 (50)}) 19. Ne4 Bxe4 {Getting rid of the powerful
knight seems to be the best decision,} ({considering the alternatives: 1)} 
19... h5 20. Nxc5 hxg4 21. Rfd1 cxb5 22. Nxb7 Qc2 23. Qxc2 Bxc2 24. Nxd8 Bxd1
25. Bd5+ Kh8 26. Rxd1 Nxe2+ 27. Kf1 Nc3 {1/2-1/2 Harika,D (2487)-Atakisi,U 
(2340)/Skopje 2014/CBM 159 Extra (59)} 28. Ne6 Re8 29. Bxe5 fxe5 30. Bc6 Rxe6
31. Rd8+ Kh7 32. axb5 $16) ({2)} 19... Be7 {1-0 Mchedlishvili,M (2633)-Anurag,
M (2426)/Baku 2013/CBM 156 Extra} 20. Rfd1 $16) 20. Bxe4 Qd7 21. Nxe5 fxe5 {
and here in the game 1/2-1/2 Machlik,E (1855)-Baraeva,M (2136)/Al Ain 2013/CBM
158 Extra (45)} {white could have obtained clear advantage with the simple.}
22. bxc6 bxc6 23. Be3 $14 {[%csl Rc6,Gd4,Ge4,Re5]} *

