1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 Bf5 6. Ne5 Nbd7 7. Nxc4 Qc7 {In
this chapter we will quickly cover the minor lines in 7...Qc7.} 8. g3 e5 (8...
Rd8 {is rare and does not really make sense unless black will answer Bf4 with
e5 anyway.} 9. Bf4 Qc8 $6 (9... e5 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Qc1 {-8...e5}) 10. f3 {
[%cal Ge2e4]} Nc5 {1-0 Mikhalevski,V (2614)-Vojinovic,G (2447)/Wheeling 2010/
CBM 136 Extra} 11. e4 $1 Bh3 12. Be3 g6 13. Qc2 Bxf1 14. Kxf1 Ne6 15. Rd1 Bg7
16. Kg2 O-O 17. b4 $16 {[%csl Rc8,Rd8,Rf8,Rg7,Rg8] Black is confined to the
7th rank - not a good deal for him.}) 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Bf4 Nfd7 (10... Rd8 {is
the alternative to Nfd7. Black does not want to waste time in the opening with
Nfd7, so he is willing to give up the bishop pair to complete his development:}
11. Qc1 Bd6 {[%cal Ge8g8]} 12. Nxd6+ Qxd6 {[%csl Gf1,Gf4]} 13. Bg2 O-O {Black
completed his development and is well centralized.} (13... Qe7 14. O-O a5 {
unpins the queen, but white can force a favorable endgame with} 15. Qe3 $1 Nc4
16. Qxe7+ Kxe7 17. e4 Be6 18. Rfe1 h6 (18... Nxb2 19. e5 $16) 19. b3 Nd2 (19...
g5 20. Bc1 $1 {[%cal Gc1a3]}) (19... Nb2 20. Bc7 $16) 20. Nd5+ $1 cxd5 21. Bxd2
b6 22. exd5 Nxd5 {1/2-1/2 Hort,V (2615)-Mokry,K (2435)/Sumperk 1984/MCL (28)}
23. Rad1 $1 $16 {[%cal Gd2a5]}) 14. O-O a5 {[%csl Ga5,Gb4] This move stops
white from gaining space on the queenside.} ({In case of} 14... Rfe8 {white is
the one who pushes the pawn first:} 15. a5 {[%cal Ga5a6]} Qb4 (15... a6 16. Na4
$14 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Ga4c5] is more solid.}) 16. a6 {[%csl Rc6]} b5 17. Bxe5
Rxe5 18. Bxc6 h6 19. Bf3 $14 {and white was a clear pawn up in 1-0 Jobava,B 
(2678)-Gretarsson,H (2452)/Porto Carras 2011/CBM 146 (70)}) {Among several
possible plans, including Qe3 and Rd1, I would recommend the following knight
maneouvre:} 15. Nd1 $1 {[%csl Ra5,Re5][%cal Gd1e3,Gc1c3,Ye3c4] instead of
going to e3 with queen and leaving the knight on c3, white wants to reverse
their positions. Indeed the knight would stand perfectly on e3, while the
queen targets both a5 and e5 from c3.} Qe6 (15... Nd5 16. Ne3 Nxe3 17. Bxe3 $14
{[%csl Ge3,Gg2][%cal Ge3b6,Gc1c3] is very comfortable for white too, though
perhaps a lesser evil for black compared to the text.}) 16. Ne3 Be4 17. f3 Bd5
18. Qc3 Rfe8 19. Rfd1 $14 {[%csl Rd5]} h6 $6 (19... Ng6 $142 20. Bg5 b6 $14)
20. Nc2 Ng6 21. e4 Nxf4 22. gxf4 $16 {1-0 Stohl,I (2540)-Zurek,M (2455)/
Olomouc 1998/CBM 067/[Huebner,R] (50)}) 11. Bg2 Be6 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ge6c4]
This is an old move. Black wants to alleviate the pressure on e5 without
playing f7-f6 which weakens the kingside.} ({Another alternative of older date
is} 11... Be7 12. O-O O-O {[%csl Gc3,Gc4,Gf4,Gg2] where black completes his
development, but does nothing to challenge white's central domination.} 13. Qc1
$1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gc1e3,Gc3d5] The usual maneouvre.} f6 {It turns out that
black has to play this move sooner or later.} 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 (14... fxe5 15. Nd5
$1 Qd8 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. Bg5 Qe6 18. a5 h6 19. Be3 $14 {1-0 Razuvaev,Y (2485)
-Bronstein,D (2495)/Yaroslavl 1982/EXT 1999 (59)}) 15. Nd5 Qd6 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7
17. Qc3 $14 {[%csl Gc3,Gf4,Gg2]} a5 18. Be3 Rfe8 19. Bc5 Qf7 {here white
activated is pawn majority:} 20. e4 Be6 21. f4 Nd7 22. Bf2 $16 {with an ideal
position for white in 1-0 Soffer,R (2535)-Mencinger,V (2385)/Bled 1995/EXT
1998 (74)}) ({In the light of variations with long castle we have seen in
CHAPTER 8,} 11... O-O-O $2 {is very risky. White has a thematic:} 12. Nd5 $1
cxd5 13. Nxe5 Bb4+ {This intermediate move does not change much.} (13... Nxe5
14. Rc1 Bc5 15. O-O $18) 14. Kf1 Nxe5 15. Rc1 Bc5 16. b4 Kb8 17. Rxc5 Qe7 18.
h4 $16 {1-0 Bogner,S (2502)-Toth,E (2392)/Winterthur 2009/CBM 132 Extra (37)})
12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. O-O {Black could now, of course, fortify the knight with
f7-f6, transposing to CHAPTER 8, so let us just see which alternatives he has
at his disposal:} Qa5 {[%csl Ga5,Gb4][%cal Ga5e5] This looks really good for
black at first as he gets rid of the pin and blocks the queenside. However, we
know that playing with the queen in the opening too much can lead to
development difficulties.} ({If black continues developing normally with} 13...
Be7 {white has} 14. Qc2 $1 {[%cal Yc3b5,Yb5d4,Rc3d5] /\15.Nb5-d4, 15.Nd5} Rd8 (
14... Qa5 15. Nb5 $1) (14... a6 15. Rfd1 O-O 16. Ne4 (16. Nd5 Bxd5 17. Rxd5 $14
) 16... Qa5 $6 (16... f6 17. Nc5 Bxc5 18. Qxc5 $14) 17. b4 $1 Bxb4 18. Rab1 Ng6
19. Bd6 Bxd6 20. Nxd6 Qh5 21. Rxb7 $16 {1-0 Dubessay,B (2310)-Benitah,Y (2392)/
Caen 2011/CBM 144 Extra (39)}) 15. Rfd1 O-O 16. Nb5 Qb8 {This is the most
accurate.} ({A famous game between two World Championship rivals continued} 
16... Rxd1+ 17. Rxd1 Qa5 18. Nd4 Bc8 {and here Alekhine used Capablanca's idea:
} 19. b4 $1 Qc7 (19... Bxb4 20. Nb3 Qc7 21. Qe4 Bc3 (21... Bd6 22. Qd4 $18 {
Alekhine} g5 23. Bxg5 Be7 24. Bxe7 Qxe7 25. Qxa7) 22. Rc1 $16) 20. b5 c5 21.
Nf5 $16 {with a large positional advantage for white in 1-0 Alekhine,A-Euwe,M/
Netherlands 1935/MainBase/[ChessBase] (30)}) 17. Nd4 Bd7 18. a5 a6 {White's
position is very pleasant and he can harrass black pieces with his knight:} 19.
Nf5 Bf6 20. Nd6 Be6 21. Ne4 Be7 22. Qc3 f6 23. Ng5 $1 $14 {[%csl Re5]}) 14. Ne4
Rd8 15. Qc2 Be7 {It seemed like black had nothing to worry about, when great
Capa uncorked} 16. b4 $1 {Sacrificing pawn for initiative.} Bxb4 17. Qb2 {
[%csl Gb2][%cal Gb2b7,Gb2g7]} f6 {1-0 Capablanca,J-Euwe,M/Amsterdam 1931/HCL 
(35)  and here he had even stronger} 18. Bxe5 fxe5 19. Rab1 $16 Rd4 20. e3 Rc4
21. Ng5 Bf5 {with a point:} 22. Rfd1 $3 Bxb1 23. Qxb1 $40 {[%csl Re8][%cal
Gg5h7,Gb1d3,Gd3d7]} *

