1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 Bf5 6. Ne5 Nbd7 7. Nxc4 Qc7 8.
g3 e5 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Bf4 Nfd7 11. Bg2 {Here we are at the critical line in
the Classical Slav. Morozevich's idea} g5 $5 {forces a trade of the strong
dark-squared bishop (since 12.Bxg5?? loses the knight on c4). Once this bishop
is gone, black will have a good chance to dominate dark squares such as b4, c5,
e5 etc. Having this in mind, white usually play} 12. Ne3 {[%cal Gf4g5,Ge3f5]} (
12. Bxe5 Nxe5 13. Qd4 f6) ({and} 12. Nxe5 gxf4 13. Nxd7 O-O-O {are the
alternatives.}) 12... gxf4 13. Nxf5 {[%csl Yb4,Yc5,Ge4,Ye5,Gf5,Rf7,Rh7]
basically trading white dark-squared for black light-squared bishop. With his
knight firmly positioned on f5, white controls a lot of squares in the center
of the board. In addition, white's pawn structure is a bit better as black has
isolated pawns on f7 and h7.} O-O-O {[%cal Gd8d1] Black king can find safety
only on the queenside.} ({Other moves like} 13... fxg3 14. hxg3 O-O-O 15. Qc2)
({or} 13... Ng6 14. Qc2 O-O-O 15. O-O {usually just lead to transposition to
one of the lines after 13...0-0-0.}) 14. Qc2 ({It has to be said that} 14. gxf4
$2 {is a very risky operation in the view of} Nc5 15. Qc2 Nc4 $36 {[%cal Gc7f4,
Gd8d2] and black has dangerous threats for a mere pawn.}) {The position is
rich in possiblities and we will take a look at different options for black.
The main line is} 14... Nc5 {[%csl Gc5,Ge5][%cal Gd8d1]} ({Another common
approach by black is to play a useful waiting move:} 14... Kb8 {and here white
has a wide choice of options, though I would recommend the simple} 15. O-O ({
It seemed like white could hold onto his extra pawn after} 15. gxf4 Nc4 16. e3
{[%csl Gf4]} Nc5 17. Rd1 {[%csl Gd2]} Rxd1+ 18. Nxd1 Qa5+ 19. Nc3 {until
Nakamura found the equalizer} Qb6 $1 $11 {1/2-1/2 Wang,H (2726)-Nakamura,H 
(2778)/Istanbul 2012/CBM 151 (50)}) ({The main alternative is} 15. O-O-O $5 {
which is possible since black did not play Nc5 earlier. The king is relatively
safe on the queenside and white should keep a small edge due to positional
factors. Two games of Indian GM Gupta were significant for this line:} Ng4 {
[%csl Rf2][%cal Gg4f2]} (15... fxg3 16. hxg3 Bb4 17. Kb1 Qa5 18. Na2 Nf6 (18...
Nb6 19. b3 $14) 19. Nd4 Be7 $2 20. f4 Neg4 21. Qxc6 $1 {[%csl Ra5,Rb8][%cal
Gg2b7] A nice idea that black probably missed when playing Be7; we will see
variations of sacrifice on c6 throughout this chapter.} Nd5 22. Nb3 Qb6 23.
Qxb6 $18 {with a winning endgame in 1-0 Gupta,A (2652)-Javakhishvili,L (2454)/
Caleta 2012/CBM 147 (72)}) 16. Ne4 Qe5 17. h3 Nh6 18. Nd4 Bg7 $2 {[%csl Gd6]
Missing an important tactical nuance.} (18... fxg3 19. Nxg3 Qc5 20. e3 $14 {
[%csl Gd4,Rf7,Rh6,Rh7]}) 19. gxf4 Qxf4+ 20. e3 Qc7 21. Nd6 $1 $40 {[%csl Gd6]
[%cal Gd4c6] 1-0 Gupta,A (2593)-Romanov,E (2654)/Bad Wiessee 2013/EXT 2014 (27)
}) {A very sharp position with heterogenous castles has arisen. Black can
either start his pawn storm immediately with} 15... fxg3 ({or go into
prevention mode with} 15... Ng6 16. Rfc1 {[%cal Gc1c7]} a5 {but white can
start the attack with} 17. b4 $1 {anyway. Black now has to defend carefully:}
axb4 (17... Bxb4 {is not as good. White's attack unfolds easily after} 18. Nd5
$1 Qe5 19. Nxb4 axb4 20. Rab1 Qa5 (20... c5 {[%cal Gg2b7] opens up the bishop
and gives white motifs along the long diagonal.} 21. e3 fxg3 (21... fxe3 22. f4
$1 $16) 22. hxg3 Rc8 (22... h5 23. f4 Qe6 24. Rxb4 $18) 23. Rd1 $16) (20... Ne7
21. Qc4 $1 Nxf5 22. Qxb4 $18) 21. Nd6 Nde5 22. Nc4 Nxc4 23. Qxc4 $14 {[%csl
Gb1,Rb8,Gc1,Gc4,Gg2] putting black under serious pressure in 1-0 Caruana,F 
(2649)-Ni Hua (2724)/Dagomys 2009 (52)}) 18. Nb5 Qe5 19. Nbd4 {[%csl Rc6][%cal
Gd4c6] Threatening to rip through black's defences with Nxc6 sacrifice.} Bc5 {
[%cal Rc1c5] All this happened in a top level game 1-0 Carlsen,M (2772)-Wang,Y
(2736)/Nanjing 2009/CBM 133. After analyzing this position, I came to a
