far, so it is hard to make any definite conclusions.} ({The main line goes
like this:} 18. Rxd8+ Qxd8 19. Rd1 Qf6 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Gf6f5,Gf6h4,Gf6b2]} 20.
Bh3 Kb8 21. Qd2 {with complex play. White has won some games, but I think that
black should be able to hold this position with accurate play. A recent top
level game between Wesley So and Mamedyarov was drawn, for example.}) 18... Kb8
{The most solid response.} ({Black can also go for h5-h4 with} 18... Ng6 {but
then white has} 19. Rd4 $1 {meaning that} h4 {has to come with a price of a
pawn, at least temporarily.} ({if} 19... Rxd4 {then} 20. exd4 $1 $16) 20. Nxh4
Nxh4 21. Rxh4 Rxh4 22. gxh4 Qe5 {[%cal Gf8d6]} 23. Rd1 Bd6 24. Kf1 $1 {[%csl
Gf1] King is completely safe here.} Rh8 25. Ne2 Rxh4 {Black returned the pawn,
but white gains the initiative:} 26. Nd4 $14 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gd4f3,Gd4c6]} Rh5
27. Qc4 $1 {[%cal Gc4f7,Gb2b4] Even in such a simple position, white can pose
problems for black.} Rh8 28. b4 axb4 29. a5 $1 $40 {[%csl Rc6,Rc8][%cal Ga5a6]
White has a serious attack all of a sudden and black collapses quickly.} Na6 $4
30. Nxc6 $18 {Tomashevsky,E (2695)-Shimanov,A (2643) Vladivostok RUS 2014}) 19.
Rd4 Ne6 20. Rxd8+ Qxd8 21. Rd1 Qc7 $1 {Very precise play by Mamedov.} ({It is
tempting to bring the queen to f6} 21... Qf6 {to participate in kingside play,
